{[%evp 0,31,19,11,37,-18,3,-30,7,8,8,2,43,37,54,47,56,53,26,23,12,41,56,21,21,
25,27,11,9,16,16,12,34,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 {This move order has its
advantages and drawbacks. In specific lines of the Bogo-Indian and Catalan, it
can be to White's benefit that he isn't committed to an early Nf3. 3.g3 also
has the bonus of preventing the Queen's Indian Defence. The only slight
drawback can be seen after 3...c5, when White is committed to the Fianchetto
Variation against the Modern Benoni.} c5 4. d5 $1 (4. Nf3 {I played many games
with this move with varying success. In general, I don't like the forcing
nature of some of the modern lines arising after 3.Nf3.}) 4... exd5 5. cxd5 d6
6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 (8. e4 O-O 9. Nge2 $15 {would be an inferior way
to develop. The knight is misplaced on e2 since it does not support the e4-e5
advance.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O {In our repertoire I offer two approaches for White:
one principled theoretical option and one (the one I prefer!) based on ideas
and understanding, enabling us to get out of book quickly! There exist three
different philosophies of playing with White: 1) The "old" plan - playing Nd2
(-c4) against everything, with the idea of advancing in the centre with e4, f4,
etc. Practice has shown that Black gets excellent counterplay against this. 2)
The modern trend - playing Bf4 and continuing depending on Black's reply. 3)
Playing useful waiting moves (Re1, h3, or a4) and only then deciding on a
concrete plan.} Re8 {In this lesson, we do not study the theory, but rather
the typical ideas of the Fianchetto System of the Modern Benoni.} (9... Nbd7
10. Bf4 (10. h3) (10. a4) (10. Re1) 10... Qe7 {I noticed an amazing thing
about these variations: White does not have strong play, but he has
potentially strong counter-play! For example, his strategy would fail if White
tries to play aggressively. If, however, White plays useful waiting moves and
Black is the one trying to take the initiative, then White often develops a
massive initiative!} (10... Ne8 {Here, different ideas are interesting.} 11.
Bg5 $5 {looks tempting since Black probably has to return with the knight.} (
11. Qd2 $5) (11. Re1 Rb8 12. a4 a6 13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Qxb6 15. Ra2 {is
playable but it looks acceptable for Black.}) (11. e4 $5) 11... Nef6 {might be
the best reply.}) 11. h3 {A typical useful waiting move, taking g4 under
control.} ({If White tries to play more directly with} 11. Nd2 {then Black
already gets a very good game with} Nh5 12. Be3 f5 $15 ({or} 12... Ne5 13. h3
a6 14. a4 f5 $15)) {If Black tries to do something active, this will backfire:}
11... Nh5 12. Bg5 Bf6 {Is it good for White to exchange the dark-squared
bishops? In the g3-Benoni, it's always good to exchange the dark-squared
bishops! It's not easy to describe in words why. One reason is that without
the dark-squared bishops, it's easier for White to advance his majority in the
centre.} (12... f6 13. Bd2 (13. Be3 $4 Nxg3 $19) 13... f5 14. Ng5 $5 {[%cal
Yg5e6]}) (12... Nhf6 {is possibly best.}) 13. Bxf6 Nhxf6 {And now for example}
14. Re1 ({or} 14. Qd2 a6 15. a4 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. e4 {Black's position is
already critical.} Bd7 18. Rad1 {This has to be considered to take d4 under
control.} (18. f4 Qd4+) 18... b5 19. axb5 axb5 20. f4 Qe7 21. e5 $1 {White's
setup appeared to quiet, yet it contains a lot of energy! Black is already
lost.} Ne8 22. e6 (22. Rfe1) 22... Bc8 23. f5 b4 24. Ne4 $18) 14... Ne5 15.
Nxe5 Qxe5 16. e3 $5 {A clever idea, keeping d4 under control and preparing f4,
followed by e4 without giving the queen access to d4.} (16. e4) (16. a4 {
is playable, yet it's not necessary to prevent ...b5.} a6 17. e3 (17. e4 Bd7
18. f4 $5 (18. Kh2) 18... Qd4+ 19. Kh2 $16) 17... Bd7 18. f4 Qe7 19. e4 b5 20.
e5 Ne8 21. Qd2 b4 22. Ne4 $18) 16... Nd7 (16... Bd7 17. f4 Qe7 18. e4 Ne8 19.
e5 $16) 17. f4 Qe7 18. e4 a6 19. e5 $16 (19. Qd2 Rb8 20. e5 $16)) (9... h6 10.
Bf4 (10. h3 $5) ({After} 10. e4 {Black is happy after} Bg4) (10. Re1 $5) 10...
Na6 ({If} 10... g5 11. Bd2 Bf5 ({or} 11... Na6 12. h4 g4 13. Ne1) 12. h4 g4 {
Black's pawns are getting overextended, and his position is left containing
too many weaknesses.} 13. Nh2 (13. Ne1 {[%cal Ye1d3,Yd3f4]}) 13... Na6 14. Re1)
(10... Nh5 11. Bd2 f5 {After ...h6, this does not work.} 12. e4 $1 f4 {This
has to be met by energetic play.} (12... fxe4 13. Nxe4 (13. Nh4 $5) 13... Bxb2
14. Bxh6 Bxa1 15. Bxf8 $18) (12... Bxc3 $2 13. Bxc3 fxe4 14. Nh4 $18) 13. Nh4
$1 (13. Ne2 $5) (13. e5 $5) 13... Qe8 14. Bf3 {Black is not in time to
stabilise his position.} (14. Re1 g5 15. Nf5 $18) (14. Nb5 $3 Qxb5 15. Nxg6 $18
) 14... Nf6 15. Bxf4 $18 (15. gxf4) (15. e5 dxe5 16. Qc2 {can be considered as
an idea.}) 15... g5 16. Bxd6 gxh4 17. e5 Nfd7 18. Bh5 Qd8 19. e6 $18 (19. Bxf8)
(19. f4)) 11. Re1 {White is gathering energy by improving his position.} Bg4 (
11... Ng4 12. e4 {I like this best, with the idea} ({I am not too happy with} 
12. h3 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bd2 f5) (12. Qc1 $5) 12... Nc7 13. h3 Ne5 14. Nxe5
dxe5 15. Be3 {and a nice advantage for White.}) 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 (13. exf3
{can be interesting, but not in this particular position.}) 13... Nc7 14. e4 b5
{When White has already strong play in the centre, ...b5 is not a good idea.}
15. e5 $1 ({A tactical idea that needs to be kept in mind is} 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16.
e5 Qb6 (16... Qd8 $2 17. d6 $1 $18 (17. exf6 $14))) 15... dxe5 16. Bxe5 {
After having achieved the central breakthrough, White has a decisive advantage.
} b4 17. Bxc7 (17. Ne4 $2 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 Qd6 $11) (17. d6 $18)
