{White demonstrates a typical strategy in this nice game (which resembles a
g3-Benoni): countering Black's queenside expansion with energetic play in the
centre and on the kingside!} 1. d4 $1 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. c4
Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 (7. d5 $5 exd5 8. Nh4 c6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nf5) 7... c5 8.
d5 exd5 9. Nh4 Ne4 10. cxd5 Bxh4 11. Bxe4 Bf6 12. Nc3 d6 {In this theoretical
line of the Queen's Indian, we get a Benoni structure. Typically, White
concentrates on active piece in this line.} 13. Bf4 a6 $6 {This is too slow.
White can neutralise ...b5-b4 by vacating the e4-square for his knight.} (13...
Re8 14. Qc2 g6 15. Bg2 Na6 16. Ne4 Be5 17. Bxe5 Rxe5 18. Nc3 $14) (13... Qe7 $5
14. Qc2 g6 15. Bg2 Nd7 16. Ne4 Be5 17. Bg5 f6 18. Bh6 $16) 14. Qc2 g6 (14... h6
15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Bf5) 15. Bg2 Bg5 16. Qd2 $1 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 {Now Black must
lose time to be able to develop the knight.} Qe7 18. Ne4 Rd8 19. Rad1 $1 {
White prepares Rd3-e3.} Kg7 (19... Qe5 $2 20. Qh4 Nd7 21. f4 Qxb2 22. Nxd6 Rab8
23. Nxb7 Rxb7 24. Qxd8+ $18) 20. Rd3 $1 Qe5 21. Qd2 $6 $16 {Not bad, but 21.
Qh4 was better.} (21. Qh4 $1 Nd7 22. f4 Qxb2 23. Nxd6 c4 24. Rdd1 Nc5 25. Nxb7
Nxb7 26. d6 $18) (21. Qxe5+ dxe5 22. Rb3 Bxd5 23. Rxb6 Nd7 24. Rd6 Bxe4 25.
Bxe4 Nf6 $11) 21... f6 (21... Nd7 22. f4 Qe7 23. g4 $1 $16 {A very strong
positional move - now ...Nf6 is met by Qc3 followed by g5. Also, White's rook
might come to h3.} Kg8 24. g5 $18 {Black is completely restricted - White has
a winning advantage.}) 22. g4 $1 g5 23. h4 $18 (23. Ng3 $1 {was also very
strong.} Bc8 24. Re3 Qd4 25. Qc2 Ra7 26. Re4 $18 {Houdini}) 23... gxh4 24. f4
Qe7 25. Rh3 Nd7 26. Rxh4 Bc8 27. Qc3 b5 28. g5 b4 29. Qh3 Kh8 30. Qe6 $1 Qf8
31. g6 h6 32. Qh3 1-0

