{[%evp 0,33,19,11,20,-7,3,-30,2,2,13,11,39,39,60,56,49,23,23,11,41,54,55,44,42,
57,93,59,70,69,90,53,46,55,55,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 ({We can also reach our
system against the move order} 2... c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 {
Against the Modern Benoni, we have the option to play more aggressive systems,
though we can also transpose our repertoire with} 6. Nf3 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2
O-O 9. O-O) 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 (5... b5 6. e4 $1 Nxe4 (6... Qe7 7.
f3 $1 a6 8. a4 $1 $16 (8. Bh3 $5 Bb7 (8... g6 9. Ne2 Bg7 10. d6 $1 Qe5 11. O-O
$16) 9. Ne2 d6 10. a4 $1 b4 11. Nd2 Nbd7 12. Nc4 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. a5 $1
Rd8 15. O-O Be7 16. Nf4 Nd7 (16... O-O 17. Ng2 $16) 17. Ng2 $1 O-O 18. Ne3 $16)
(8. Nh3 $5 $16)) 7. Bg2 Nd6 8. Bf4 $1 {White has a very strong initiative for
the pawn; for example :} Be7 (8... b4 9. Ne2 Ba6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. a3
bxa3 13. Rxa3 $16) 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Na6 (10... Bb7 11. Re1 Re8 12. Nc3 a6 13.
Ng5 $3 $18 Bxg5 14. Bxd6 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 {Black can hardly move.}) (10... Re8
11. Re1 Na6 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Nd2 $1 Bf8 14. Rxe8 Qxe8 15. Bxd6 Bxd6 16. Nxb5 $16
) 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Nc3 b4 13. Bxd6 Bxd6 14. Ne4 Be7 15. d6 Bf6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6
17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rad8 19. Qd5 $16) 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O
{We have reached the basic tabia of the g3-Benoni. Black can choose between
several possible continuations.} Re8 $1 {This is the main line - Black retains
several different options of how to continue on his next move.} (9... a6 10. a4
Nbd7 $5 (10... Re8 11. Bf4 Ne4 (11... Bf5 12. Nd2 (12. Bg5 $5 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6
(13... Bxf6 14. Nd2 Bc8 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Qd2 h5 (17... Kh7 18. Ncxd6
$18) 18. b4 $18) 14. Nd2 $14)) 12. Ra3 $1 $14 {transposes to the line 9...Re8
10. Bf4 a6.} Bf5 13. Nd2 Nxc3 14. bxc3 g5 15. e4 $1 (15. Be3 Rxe3 16. fxe3 Bg6
17. Nc4) 15... gxf4 16. exf5 fxg3 17. hxg3 Nd7 18. a5) 11. Bf4 (11. h3 $5) (11.
a5 Re8 12. Nd2 b5 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. Nb3 Nc4 $132) 11... Qe7 (11... Ne8 12. Qd2
$1 {In the g3-Benoni it's always a good idea to exchange the dark-squared
bishops!} b6 (12... Qe7 13. Bh6 $5 (13. Bg5 $5 f6 14. Bf4 $5 (14. Bh6)) (13.
Rab1 $5 Nc7 14. Rfc1 (14. b4 $2 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Nxd5 $15) (14. Bh6 $5 b5 15. Bxg7
Kxg7 16. axb5 axb5 17. b4 $16 cxb4 18. Rxb4 Nc5 19. Nd4 $16 (19. Nxb5)) 14...
b5 (14... Ne5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. b4 (17. Re1 Bd7 (17... f5 18. e3
Bd7 19. a5 (19. f4 Qg7 20. e4 fxe4 21. Nxe4)) 18. e4)) 15. b4 $1 $16 cxb4 16.
Rxb4 a5 17. Re4 $1 (17. Rxb5 $5 $18) 17... Bxc3 18. Rxe7 Bxd2 19. Nxd2 $18))
13. Bh6 $5 (13. Rab1 $5) 13... Qe7 14. Bxg7 Nxg7 15. e4 Rb8 16. Rfe1 b5 17.
axb5 axb5 18. e5 $1 (18. b4 $1 cxb4 19. Na2 b3 20. Nb4 $16) 18... dxe5 19. d6
Qd8 (19... Qe6 20. Ng5) 20. Nd5 $18) 12. Rb1 $1 {With the inclusion of a4-a6,
it makes a lot more sense to prepare b4, because b6 is weakened, and this
square might be used by our rook! Let's look at some sample lines:} (12. e4 $1
Ng4 13. Bg5 $1 $14 f6 (13... Qe8 14. h3 Nge5 15. Nd2 $16 Nd3 16. Nc4 Nxb2 17.
Nxb2 Bxc3 18. Nc4 $1 $16) 14. Bc1 Nde5 15. Nh4) (12. Re1 $5) (12. h3 $5) 12...
Re8 $5 (12... Nh5 13. Bg5 Qe8 (13... Bf6 {We already know that we can happily
exchange the dark-squared bishops, and gain an advantage.} 14. Bxf6 ({However,
} 14. Bd2 {is also very good in this position since the knight on h5 is
misplaced.} Ne5 15. Re1 $16 {[%csl Rh5]} (15. Ne4 Bg7 16. Bg5 f6 17. Nxe5 Qxe5
(17... dxe5 18. Be3 $16) 18. Bd2 f5 19. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%cal Yg5e6]})) 14... Nhxf6
15. Re1 Ng4 16. Qc1 (16. b4 $5 Ne3 17. Qd2) (16. Nd2 $16) 16... Nge5 17. Nd2 f5
18. f4 $1 Nf7 19. e4 $18) 14. Qc1 f5 (14... Ne5 15. Ne4 $1 (15. Re1) (15. Bh6
Bd7 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qc3 $1 $16) 15... Nxf3+ (15...
Qd7 16. b4 $16) 16. exf3 $1 Qd7 17. g4 $16) 15. b4 Nhf6 16. bxc5 Nxc5 17. Nd2
$16) (12... h6 13. b4 cxb4 (13... Re8 $1 14. a5 Kh7 $13 15. Qc2 $1 $16 {
SUPER SOS !! .. GENERALLY WHEN I SEE A Kh7 move..i play Qc2 !!} (15. Na4) 15...
cxb4 16. Rxb4 Nc5 17. Nd2 $5 (17. Nd4 $5 Nh5 18. Bd2 Bd7 19. Nb3 $3 Rac8 20.
Qa2 $3 {at first it seems that black has very active play..but in fact he is
much worse} Rc7 21. Nxc5 Rxc5 22. Re4 Qd8 23. Rxe8 Bxe8 24. Ne4 Rc7 25. Bb4 Bf8
26. Qa3 Rd7 27. Rc1 $16 {very nice play ..just with pieces..without pawns !!})
17... Nh5 (17... Bd7 18. Nc4 $16 Bf5 19. Qd2) 18. Be3 Bf5 19. Qb2 Rac8 20. Rc1
$16 Nf6 (20... Rc7 21. g4) (20... Bd7 21. Bd4 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Nf6 23. Nc4 $16 (
23. Rb4 $16)) 21. Bd4 $18) 14. Rxb4 Nc5 15. Qc1 g5 (15... Kh7 16. Qa3 $16) 16.
Be3 $16) 13. a5 (13. b4 cxb4 14. Rxb4 Nc5 15. Nd4 Nh5 $5 (15... Bd7 $6 16. Rb6
$14) 16. Be3 Bd7 17. Qd2 $14 (17. Qb1 Rac8 18. Rc1 $14)) (13. h3 $5 h6 14. e4
g5 15. Bd2 $14 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. b4 $16 (17. Kh2 Bd7 18. f4 gxf4 19. Bxf4
Qe7 20. Qd2 Kh7 21. Rbe1 Nh5 22. e5 Nxf4 23. gxf4 dxe5 24. d6 Qd8 25. fxe5
Bxe5+ 26. Rxe5 Rxe5 27. Rxf7+ $1 Kg8 (27... Kg6 28. Rf4 $1 $18) 28. Qf4 $18) (
17. a5 $16)) 13... h6 (13... Ng4 14. Bg5 (14. h3 Nge5 15. Ne4 $5 $14) 14... Bf6
(14... f6 15. Bf4 $16) 15. Bxf6 Ngxf6 16. Nd2 $16) 14. b4 Nh5 (14... Rb8 15.
bxc5 Nxc5 16. Rb6 Nfe4 $1 $132) (14... cxb4 15. Rxb4 Nc5 16. Qc1 g5 (16... Kh7
17. Qa3 $16) 17. Be3 $16) 15. Bd2 cxb4 16. Rxb4 Nc5 17. Qc1 Kh7 18. Qa3 $16) (
9... Bg4 $2 {If Black were allowed to play ...Bxf3, his position would be
acceptable. But after} 10. Nd2 $1 {the bishop is misplaced on g4.} Qd7 (10...
Nbd7 $4 11. h3 $18) (10... Na6 11. h3 Bd7 12. a4 $1 {We can stop ...b5,
knowing that the knight on b4 is completely harmless. For example} (12. Nc4 $5)
12... Nb4 13. Nc4 Qe7 14. Bf4 Ne8 15. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rb4]}) 11. f3 $1 $16 (11.
a4 $1 $16 Na6 (11... Bh3 12. Nc4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qe7 14. Bf4 Rd8 (14... Ne8 15.
Qb3 $16 Na6 16. f3 Nb4 17. Rad1 Rd8 18. e4 $18) 15. h4 $18 {White is already
winning according to the computer - +2.0!} (15. e4 $1 Nh5 16. Qf3 $16)) 12. Nc4
Rfd8 13. Bf4 Ne8 14. Qd2 $16) 11... Bh3 12. Bxh3 Qxh3 13. Nc4 Ne8 (13... Nh5
14. Ne4 $18) 14. Bf4 $16) (9... b6 $6 {This is very slow - it also weakens
some light squares on the queenside.} 10. Bf4 (10. Re1 $5) 10... Ba6 11. Re1 $1
Nh5 (11... b5 12. e4 b4 13. Na4 $16) 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. e4 h6 14. Bd2 Nd7 15. a4
c4 (15... Rfe8 16. Qc2 $16) 16. Qc2 Nc5 17. Nb5 $16 Bxb5 18. axb5 Nd3 19. Re3
Nxb2 {[%csl Rb2]} 20. e5 $18 (20. Bc3 $18)) (9... Na6 $5 10. Bf4 (10. Re1 $5
$14 {with typical Benoni play, is also good!}) 10... Nc7 11. e4 $1 {SUPER SOS
! When the goes for ...Na6-Nc7 in the g3-Benoni, it abandons the control of
some important central squares. So, the breakthrough e4-e5 gains in strength!}
Bg4 (11... b5 $2 12. e5 $16) 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 $14 {White is better in this
position BECAUSE BLACK CANNOT GET HIS KNIGHT to d7 without making some major
concessions!} Nfe8 (13... Nd7 $2 14. Bxd6 $18) (13... Qe7 14. e5 $1 Nfe8 15.
exd6 Nxd6 16. Ne4 $3 Nxe4 (16... Be5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Nxc5 Qxb2 19. Rb1 Qxa2
20. Nd7 $18) (16... Ncb5 17. Nxc5 $16 Bxb2 18. Rb1 $3 Nc3 19. Qb3 Nxb1 20. Qxb2
$18) 17. d6 $18) (13... Nce8 14. h4 Nd7 15. Kg2 a6 16. a4 Ne5 17. Be2 h5 18.
Qd2 Nc7 19. a5 Re8 20. Bg5 f6 (20... Bf6 21. f4 $18) 21. Bh6 $16) 14. a4 $1 $16
(14. Qd2 $5 {We can allow Black to play ...b5, when we are ready to strike in
the centre, or, we can stop his counterplay with a3. For example} b5 15. a3 a6
16. Rfe1 {White is significantly better due to the bad knight on c7.} Rb8 17.
Bg5 $1 $16 (17. b4 $2 {loses tactically:} cxb4 18. axb4 g5 $3 19. Be3 Qf6 $17)
(17. e5 $2 {is premature.} dxe5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 Nd6 $11) (17. Kg2 b4 18.
axb4 Rxb4 19. Be2 $14)) (14. Re1 $1 b5 ({If Black plays} 14... Be5 {we should
not take, since Black would take with the d-pawn and put his knight on the
excellent blockading square on d6.} 15. Be3 b5 16. Bg2 $1 b4 17. f4 $1 Bg7 18.
Na4 Nb5 19. Rc1 $2 $16) 15. a3 Rb8 16. h4 $5 h5 17. Kg2 a5 18. Rc1 b4 19. Na4
$16) 14... Na6 $2 {The knight will be irrelevant on b4!} 15. Qd2 Nb4 16. Rfe1
$16) (9... Nbd7 10. Bf4 Qe7 (10... Nb6 11. e4 $36) 11. a4 $1 (11. Re1 $1) (11.
h3 $1 Nh5 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Bxf6 Nhxf6 14. Nd2 (14. Re1)) 11... Ng4 (11... a6 12.
Rb1 $1 {transposes to 9...a6.}) 12. Bg5 $1 (12. Re1 $5 Nge5 13. Qd2 $5 (13. Qc2
$14) 13... a6 (13... Re8 14. Nb5 $14) 14. a5 (14. Rab1) 14... Rb8 15. Nxe5 Nxe5
16. Na4 Bd7 17. Nb6 Bb5 18. b4 cxb4 19. Rab1 $16) 12... f6 (12... Qe8 $4 13.
Nb5 $18) (12... Bf6 13. Bxf6 $1 {SUPER SOS! In the g3 Benoni it is GENERALLY
very good for White (and very bad for Black!) to exchange the dark-squared
bishops!} Ngxf6 14. Nd2 $1 (14. Re1 $5) 14... Ne5 15. h3 (15. Re1 $5) (15. Qc2
$5) 15... Nh5 16. e4 f5 (16... Nd3 $6 17. Nc4 Nb4 18. Re1 $16) 17. f4 Nd3 (
17... Nxg3 18. fxe5 Nxf1 19. exd6 Qxd6 20. Qxf1 fxe4 21. Qc4 $16) 18. Qf3 Nb4
