1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3
O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Bf4 Na6 11. Re1 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nd7 $1 (13... Nc7
14. e4 $1 {Now, this is strong since e4-e5 is difficult to prevent!} b5 ({
Unfortunately for Black} 14... Nd7 $2 {can no longer be played due to} 15. Bxd6
$18) 15. e5 dxe5 16. Rxe5 Rxe5 17. Bxe5 b4 18. Na4 (18. d6) 18... Nfxd5 19.
Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nxc5) 14. Ne4 (14. Bxd6 $6 Qb6 $132) 14... Ne5 15. Bg2 b5 16. a4
b4 17. Nd2 Nb8 18. Bxe5 $5 Bxe5 19. Nc4 {The knight on c4 is very strong and
Black fails to exchange it, because White can prevent ...Nd7-b6 and ...Nd7-e5.}
Bg7 20. a5 {White has the better chances. Black's majority on the queenside is
securely blockaded, while sooner or later White can advance his majority on
the kingside.} Na6 (20... Qc7 21. e4 Nd7 22. f4 {White controls b6 and e5,
securing the position of the powerful knight on c4.} Bd4+ 23. Kh2 $16) 21. Qa4
(21. e4 $1 $16) 21... Rc8 22. e3 Nc7 23. Rad1 Rb8 24. Rd3 Nb5 25. Qd1 Qd7 26.
