{[%evp 0,107,19,11,26,0,1,-30,2,2,18,18,19,36,44,38,30,36,30,39,30,31,32,17,34,
33,35,32,3,31,33,33,47,56,55,52,52,54,48,38,43,36,32,32,37,37,32,16,16,16,48,
25,41,27,24,22,28,9,10,7,6,-1,16,0,7,1,1,4,4,2,8,0,51,44,67,38,1,0,4,4,4,0,0,0,
37,51,51,34,50,42,45,44,44,44,44,44,88,95,96,103,164,164,164,171,358,378,376,
408,422,424]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 {SUPER SOS! By using the move order
with 3.g3! instead of 3.Nf3, the Bogo-Indian setups become less attractive for
Black, because we have the strong idea of developing with e3-Ne2! After 3.g3
Bb4+ 4. Bd2, the best move for Black is 4...Be7! which will transpose to the
regular Catalan. In this lesson, however, we are studying the lines in which
Black goes for genuine Bogo-Indian setups! STUDY THE GAMES VERY CAREFULLY!}
Bb4+ 4. Bd2 {4.Nd2 and 4.Nc3 are possible as well - we go for the most common
continuation, 4.Bd2.} Qe7 (4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d5) (4... Be7 $1 {Of course,
this is the best move, transposing to a regular Catalan!} 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3) (
4... a5 {Nothing changes after that - we continue with Bg2-e3-Bg2 if Black
goes for a setup with ...d6! If Black plays ...d5, we transpose to our line
with Qa4+ in the Catalan!} 5. Bg2 d6 (5... d5 $1 6. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 7. Qc2) 6. e3
O-O 7. Ne2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Nbd7 9. Nbc3 e5 10. O-O exd4 11. exd4 $1 $16 (11. Nxd4
$1)) (4... c5 $6 {This also turns out to be problematic for Black, because
White has not played Nf3 yet!} 5. Bxb4 $1 cxb4 6. Bg2 O-O 7. e3 $1 d6 (7... d5
8. Nd2 $1 b6 9. Ne2 Nc6 (9... Ba6 10. Qa4 $16 (10. Rc1 $16)) 10. O-O Bb7 11.
Rc1 Rc8 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nf4 $14) 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. O-O Bd7 10. a3 bxa3 11. Rxa3
$14 (11. Nxa3 $14)) 5. Bg2 $1 {This is much better than 5.Nf3, which
transposes to a regular Bogo-Indian, due to the plan with e3-Ne2! Whenever we
see an early ...d7-d5, we play a3! and capture on d2 with the knight!} Nc6 (
5... a5 $6 {This is a loss of time.} 6. e3 {We continue with our development.
Black will at one point have to exchange on d2.} O-O 7. Ne2 d5 (7... Bxd2+ 8.
Qxd2 $14) (7... d6 8. O-O Bxd2 9. Qxd2 $14 {followed by Nbc3, with a nice
advantage.}) 8. a3 $1 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 c6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qc2 $16 e5 12. cxd5
Nxd5 (12... cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3 $16) 13. e4 $1 N5b6 (13... N5f6 14. Nc4
$16) 14. f4 $1 $16) (5... O-O 6. e3 $1 Bxd2+ (6... d5 7. a3 $1 {This is the
typical reaction after ...d5. We force Black to exchange on d2 when we
recapture with the knight!} Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 {In setups with ...d5, the knight is
well placed on d2!} b6 (8... Nbd7 9. Ne2 $14) 9. Ne2 ({or} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Ne2
$14) 9... Bb7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nf4 $14) 7. Qxd2 $1 d6 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. Nge2 e5
10. h3 $5 {White can continue in different ways; however, h3 followed by a
possible g4, perfectly meets the requirements of the position.} (10. e4 $16) (
10. O-O $16) 10... e4 (10... c6 11. g4 $16) 11. g4 h6 12. Ng3 $16 {[%csl Re4]})
(5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 $1 {White must keep the option to develop his b1-knight to
c3 against a setup with ...d6.} (6. Nxd2 d6 $1 7. e3 ({or} 7. e4 e5 8. d5 a5 9.
Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Na6 {with interesting play for Black.}) 7... e5 8. Ne2 O-O 9.
O-O Re8 {with an acceptable game for Black.}) 6... d6 (6... d5 $5 7. Nf3 O-O (
7... Nc6 $2 8. O-O $1 dxc4 (8... O-O 9. Rc1 (9. Na3 Rd8)) 9. Na3 (9. Qc3) 9...
O-O 10. Nxc4 $16) (7... Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ 9. Nbd2 $16 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 dxc4 11. O-O
Nc6 12. e3 Na5) 8. O-O Rd8 9. Qc3 $1 $14 (9. Rc1 $14)) (6... Nc6 7. e3 (7. Nc3)
) 7. e3 (7. Nc3 e5 8. e3 exd4) 7... e5 8. Ne2 O-O (8... e4 9. Nbc3 O-O 10. h3 (
10. Nf4 c6) 10... c6 11. g4 h6) 9. Nbc3 exd4 {Now, both White can play exd4 or
Nxd4, with an advantage in both cases - take your pick!} (9... Nc6 10. Nd5 Nxd5
11. cxd5 Nb8 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. O-O) (9... c6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. h3 Re8 12. f4 (
12. Rae1 Nf8 (12... e4 13. g4 h6 14. Ng3 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. f3 exf3 17. Rxf3
Nb6) 13. f4 $5 $16 exd4 (13... exf4 14. Nxf4 $16 (14. exf4)) 14. Nxd4 $16 Be6 (
14... d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. g4 Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. f5) 15. b3 Rad8 16. e4 Bc8
17. Qf2 (17. Re3) 17... Qc7 18. g4 a5 19. Kh1 (19. g5 N6d7 20. h4) (19. Re3
Bxg4) 19... N6d7 20. Na4 Ne6 21. Nf5 (21. Nxe6 Rxe6) 21... Nec5 22. Qd4 Nf6 (
22... f6) 23. Nxc5 dxc5 24. Qxc5 Rd2 (24... Bxf5) 25. Nxg7 Kxg7 26. Qg5+ Kf8
27. Qxf6 Red8 28. e5 Kg8 29. f5 R8d3 30. Qg5+ Kf8 31. Qh6+ Kg8 32. e6 Qg3 33.
exf7+ {1-0 Kosmidis,G-Vardakas,S/Sochi RUS 2019/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 12... exf4
13. exf4 Qe3+ (13... Nb6 14. b3 Qe3+ 15. Qxe3 Rxe3 16. Kf2 Re8 17. Rfe1) 14.
Qxe3 Rxe3 15. Kf2 $16 Re8 16. g4) 10. Nxd4 $1 $16 (10. exd4 $1 $16 {see
Papaioannou-Kalesis}) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Ne5) (5... d5 6. a3 $1 (6. Nf3 $5 $14
{This is an inferior version of the Bogo-Catalan for Black.}) 6... Bxd2+ 7.
Nxd2 O-O 8. Rc1 $5 {A nice subtlety - White plays a useful move, waiting for
Black to show his hand. Instead, 8.Ngf3 is also fine. In this case, I would
abstain from e3, though it's also playable.} (8. Ngf3 $14) 8... b6 9. Nh3 $3 {
After Black has weakened the long diagonal, putting the knight on h3 is
tempting.} Bb7 10. cxd5 Bxd5 11. e4 Bb7 12. O-O Rd8 13. e5 Nd5 14. Ne4 Nd7 15.
Qe2 $16 {Black is much worse - he can never free himself with ...c7-c5 due to
the weakness of the d6 square!}) 6. e3 $1 {Black hopes for 6.Ngf3, when he
would get a comfortable line of the Bogo-Indian. However, we will see that
White gets a considerable advantage with 6.e3!} e5 {A typical move, forcing
White to immediately show his hand.} (6... O-O 7. Ne2 Bxd2+ (7... d5 8. a3 $3
Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 $3 $16 Rd8 (9... dxc4 10. Nxc4 Rd8 11. O-O $16 (11. Qc2 e5 12.
Bxc6) 11... e5 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxe5) 10. O-O b6 (10... e5 11. cxd5 $1 Nxd5
12. e4 Nf6 13. d5 Nb8 14. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 11. b4 Bb7 12. Nc3 $16 Nb8 13.
c5 $6 {This removes the pressure from d5 and allows an immediate counterplay
in the centre with ...e5!} (13. Qc2 $1 $14) (13. Rc1 $14) (13. cxd5 $1 $14 exd5
14. Qb3 c6 15. Rac1) 13... e5 $1 14. Re1 Nbd7 15. a4 Rab8 16. Nb3 e4 17. Qc1
Nf8 18. a5 Bc8 19. axb6 axb6 20. Ra7 Ne6 21. cxb6 Rxb6 22. b5 Bd7 23. Na5 Qe8
24. Nb7 Ra8 25. Rxa8 Qxa8 26. Nc5 Bxb5 27. Nxb5 Rxb5 28. Nxe6 fxe6 29. Qxc7 Qb8
30. Qe7 Qe8 31. Qc7 Qb8 32. Qe7 Qe8 33. Qc7 Qb8 {1/2-1/2 Ju Wenjun-Zhao Xue/
Jiangsu Wuxi CHN 2012/The Week in Chess 910/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 8. Qxd2 Qb4 (
8... d6 9. O-O e5 10. Nbc3 e4 (10... Bd7 11. d5 (11. Rab1) (11. Nd5 Nxd5 12.
cxd5 (12. Bxd5) 12... Nb8 (12... Nd8 13. Rac1 c6 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Rfd1 cxd5
16. Qxd5 Bc6 17. Qd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Nc6 20. Rd7 (20. Rcd1 Rfd8 21.
Nc3 Rxd6 22. Rxd6 Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Nxd8 24. Kf3 Kf8 25. Ke4 Nc6 26. Kd5 Ke7 27. a3
Kd7 28. Ne4) 20... Rab8 21. Nc3 Rfd8 22. Rcd1 Rxd7 23. Rxd7 Kf8 24. Ne4 Ke8 25.
Rc7 Nd8 26. Nd6+ Kf8 27. Rc8 (27. b4 a6 28. a4) (27. Kf3) (27. g4 h6 28. h4 a6
29. h5 (29. a4 b6 30. b4))) 13. Rac1 Na6 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Nd4) (11. Rac1 Rad8
12. h3 Rfe8 13. f4 (13. g4 h6 14. Ng3) 13... exf4 14. exf4 Qe3+ 15. Qxe3 Rxe3
16. Kf2 Ree8 17. Rfe1) (11. h3 Rfe8 12. Rac1 (12. Rae1) (12. f4 exf4 13. exf4
Qe3+ 14. Qxe3 Rxe3) (12. g4 exd4 13. exd4 h6 14. Ng3 Na5 15. b3) 12... a6 13.
Nd5 Qd8 14. Nec3) 11... Nb8 12. f4) (10... Bg4 11. h3 (11. f3) 11... Bxe2 12.
Nxe2 e4 13. Nc3) (10... Bg4 11. f3 Bd7 (11... Bh5 12. e4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14.
Qxd4 Qe5 15. Qf2 (15. Qxe5 dxe5 16. Nd5 Ne8) 15... g5 16. Rae1 Qc5 17. Qxc5
dxc5 18. e5 Nd7 19. Ne4 g4 20. f4 f5 21. Rd1 Nxe5 22. Nxc5 Nf3+ 23. Bxf3 gxf3
24. Nd7 f2+ 25. Kxf2 Bxd1 26. Nxf8 Kxf8 27. Rxd1 Ke7 28. Rd5 Ke6 29. Ke3 c6 30.
Rd3 Rc8 31. c5 b6 32. Rd6+ Ke7 33. Rh6 bxc5 34. Rxh7+ Kd6 35. Kd3 Rb8 36. Kc3
a5 37. Rh5 Ke6 38. h4 Rd8 39. Rh6+ Kd5 40. h5 Ke4 41. Rg6 Rd3+ 42. Kc2 Rf3 43.
h6 Rf2+ 44. Kc3 Rh2 45. a4 Kf3 46. b3 Rh1 (46... Ke4 47. Kc4 Rc2#) 47. Kc2 Rh2+
48. Kd3 Rh1 49. g4 fxg4 50. f5 g3 51. f6 g2 52. f7 Rd1+ 53. Kc2 Rd8 54. Rg8 Ke2
(54... Rf8) 55. Re8+ {1-0 Alexiadis-Matzakouras ,L/Kocaeli TUR 0/[,Giannis]})
12. e4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4) (10... exd4 11. exd4 (11. exd4 Bd7 12. Nf4
Rae8 13. h3 h6 14. g4) (11. Nxd4 Ne5 12. b3) 11... Re8 12. Nf4 Bf5 13. Rfe1 Qd7
14. h3 (14. d5 Ne5) (14. Nfd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Ne7 16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18.
