1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 ({Even better is} 6.
a3 $1 Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 $1) 6... O-O 7. O-O {White has a nice version of the
Catalan.} Ne4 $2 {Black wastes time moving the knight a second time.} ({If} 
7... Bxd2 {, White gets a big advantage; for example} 8. Nbxd2 Nbd7 9. Qc2 c6
10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qe2 c5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Ne5 $16) 8.
Qc2 {This is fine.} (8. Bxb4 {is another good way to play the position and to
my mind it's even more ambitious.} Qxb4 9. Qc2 $1 Qxc4 10. Qxc4 dxc4 11. Ne5
Nd6 12. Na3 Rd8 13. Rfd1 {White wins back the pawn on c4 and retains a
positional advantage.} Nd7 14. Naxc4 Nxc4 15. Nxc4 Nb6 16. Na5 c6 17. Rac1 $16)
8... Nxd2 9. Nbxd2 c6 10. e4 ({A big positional mistake would be} 10. cxd5 $2
exd5 {when White's g2-bishop is misplaced in the arising Carlsbad structure.})
10... Nd7 11. a3 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 dxe4 13. Nxe4 $16 {Black ended up with a very
bad version of the Catalan since it's impossible to free his position.} Nf6 (
13... e5 14. c5 $1 $16 (14. d5 {White's move works perfectly after} cxd5 $2 (
14... f5 $1 $132 {is less clear.} 15. d6 $2 Qe6 $17) 15. cxd5 Nf6 (15... f5 16.
d6 $1 Qe6 17. Ng5 Qxd6 18. Qb3+ $18) 16. d6 Qd8 17. Rfd1 $16)) 14. Rfe1 h6 15.
Nc3 (15. c5 $5 {is another typical idea in this position. Since Black cannot
free his position with ...d5 or ...b6, his light-squared bishop stays buried.}
Nxe4 16. Qxe4 $16 (16. Rxe4 $16) (16. Bxe4 $16)) 15... Qc7 16. b4 Rd8 17. Red1
Bd7 18. Qb3 e5 19. d5 cxd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Rxd5 Bc6 22. Rc5 Qd6 23. Bxc6 bxc6
24. Qa4 Rac8 25. Qxa7 Qd4 26. Re1 f6 27. Qa6 Qc3 28. Re3 Qc1+ 29. Kg2 Rc7 30.
Rxc6 Rxc6 31. Qxc6 Rd1 32. h4 Rh1 33. Qd5+ Kf8 34. Rd3 Qg1+ 35. Kf3 Rh2 36.
Qa8+ Kf7 37. Qb7+ Kg6 38. Qe4+ Kh5 39. Qg4# 1-0

