1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. e3 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 e5 8.
dxe5 $5 {Another possible way to play.} Qxe5 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nge2 Nc6 11. O-O {
White has a clear advantage - at one point he will play Nd5, and if ...Nxd5,
take back with the c-pawn opening the c-file against the pawn on c7.} Bf5 12.
f3 (12. Nd5 $16) 12... a6 13. Rac1 Rfe8 14. Nd5 Rac8 15. e4 $16 Bg6 16. Kh1 Nd8
17. Nec3 Nxd5 18. cxd5 f5 {Black tries to create counterplay, however, his
pieces are not placed well enough for this.} 19. f4 Qf6 20. Rce1 $16 Nf7 21. g4
fxg4 22. e5 Qh4 23. f5 Bh5 24. e6 Ne5 25. Qd4 Qe7 26. Ne4 Rf8 27. Ng3 Qh4 28.
Rxe5 dxe5 29. Qxe5 Rce8 30. Qxc7 Rf6 31. d6 Rexe6 32. fxe6 Rxf1+ 33. Bxf1 h6
34. d7 1-0

