{[%evp 0,29,19,11,23,1,1,-30,-26,-18,-9,-1,8,-42,-36,-26,-13,-13,-19,-26,-26,
-33,-5,-31,-21,-33,11,-2,-20,-3,47,-6]} 1. d4 Nf6 ({For fans of the Catalan,
this is the way to get our position after 1.d4 d5:} 1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6
4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 7. Qc2) 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 (3... Bb4+ 4. Bd2
a5 5. Bg2 d5 6. Qa4+ Bd7 7. Qc2 {is the other possible move order to get to
our position of interest!}) 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5 6. Qa4+ $1 {This move is not
so common, but it is a very interesting way to pose some problems to Black!} (
6. Nf3 {is the most common move, with a lot of theory. For example} O-O 7. Qc2
(7. O-O) (7. Qc1 $5) 7... c5 8. cxd5 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qb6 10. e3 exd5 {etc.}) 6...
Bd7 (6... Nc6 $4 7. Bxb4 $18) (6... Qd7 $6 7. Qc2 {Quite obviously, Black's
queen is standing badly on d7.} O-O 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O Bxd2 (9... Ne4 10. Bxb4
$14) 10. Nbxd2 $14) 7. Qc2 {White's idea is to prove that in the ensuing
complications, the bishop is worse on d7 compared to c8.} O-O (7... Nc6 $6 {
This movie is popular for some reason...but it's anti-positional! White gets a
comfortable advantage after} 8. Nf3 O-O (8... Ne4 $6 {Such moves are bound to
fail - Black tries to be active, neglecting his development.} 9. O-O Nxd2 10.
Nbxd2 O-O (10... Bxd2 11. Qxd2 dxc4 12. Rfc1 O-O (12... b5 $2 13. a4 $18) 13.
Rxc4 {White has a big advantage since Black does not manage to play ...c5 or ..
.e5.} Ne7 14. Ne5 $16) 11. Rfd1 Be7 12. Rac1 $14 {½-½ (27) Djukic,S-Benderac,
A/Apatin 2014}) 9. O-O Re8 (9... Bxd2 10. Nbxd2 Qe7 11. a3 Rfd8 12. Rfe1 Be8
13. Rad1 $16 {White is much better since Black cannot free his position with ..
.e5:} e5 $2 {1-0 (32) Rorrer, G-Szeberenyi,A/Budapest HUN 2024} 14. dxe5 Nxe5
15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Nc4 Qe6 18. Rd3 c6 19. Qd2 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra5,
Gd2,Rd8][%cal Ye2e4,Yc4a5,Yd2a5,Yd2d8]} (19. Red1 $18)) 10. b3 (10. Rd1 $5 $14
{is also good.} Rc8 11. Bg5 h6 $2 (11... Be7 $14) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. c5 $1 {
[%csl Rb4]} e5 14. a3 Bf5 15. Qc1 exd4 16. axb4 $16) 10... Bf8 11. Nc3 h6 12.
Rfd1 $14 {Black's position is very passive.}) (7... Bc6 $5 {This makes more
sense than 7...Nc6 - Black tries to activate his bishop.} 8. Nf3 dxc4 (8...
Bxd2+ $6 9. Nbxd2 dxc4 10. Nxc4 Be4 11. Qc3 $1 Nd5 (11... O-O $6 12. Nxa5 $16)
12. Qb3 $14) 9. Bxb4 axb4 10. Qxc4 {White has a nice version of the Open
Catalan (6...dxc4). For example} Qd6 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. O-O Bd5 13. Qc2 (13. Qd3
$14) 13... Qc6 14. Qd3 $14) 8. Nf3 c5 $5 {This is Black's best attempt for
counterplay! Both sides have several ideas, move orders, and possibilities now.
Let's analyse the most important ones!} (8... dxc4 9. Qxc4 Bxd2+ 10. Nbxd2 Bc6
(10... Nc6 11. O-O $16) 11. O-O Ne4 12. Rfd1 $14) (8... Be7 $6 9. O-O c6 (9...
Nc6 10. a3 $5 (10. Rd1 Re8 11. Bf4 $14) 10... a4 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13.
Bxc3 $16) 10. b3 (10. Rd1 Be8 11. Bf4 $14) 10... Ne4 (10... Be8 $6 11. Nc3 Na6
12. Rfd1 $16) 11. Nc3 $14) (8... Nc6 $6 9. O-O {transposes to 7...Nc6.}) 9.
