1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Be7 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 (7...
b6 $6 8. cxd5 $1 {After ...b6, taking on d5 is strong.} exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Rc1
Nbd7 11. Bf4 {White has a small, risk-free advantage - ...b6 has created some
weaknesses on the light squares and on the c-file.}) (7... c6 8. Qc2 b6 (8...
Nbd7 9. Rc1 {transposes to 7...Nbd7.}) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Rc1 Bb7 11. Ne5 $14) 8.
Qc2 c6 (8... b6 $6 9. cxd5 exd5 (9... Nxd5 10. e4 $16) 10. Qc6 Ba6 11. Nc3 $16)
9. Rc1 $5 {This is an exciting way to fight against the super-solid ...
Bb4+-Be7 system! The idea of Rc1 is to be able to play Be1 if needed, and then
develop the Nb1. However, there is a much deeper idea as well! Playing Qc2-Rc1
makes it hard for black to develop his queenside by b6-Bb7. In return, Black
is offered some attacking chances on the kingside, connected to ...Ne4-f5-Bd6
or ...Bf6,...g5, etc. However, this attack has to be conducted by Black with
only half of his army developed! As a result, a nice positional (and sometimes
tactical) battle lies ahead - precisely what we want to achieve in this super
solid positional line!} (9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nbd2 {is a simple,
playable alternative. However, I do not recommend it for players who want to
play serious chess.}) (9. Bf4 {This and 9.Rd1 are the theoretical main lines.})
9... a5 $1 {The most common move - Black fights for space and controls b4.} (
9... b6 $6 10. cxd5 (10. a4 $5 Ba6 (10... Bb7 11. a5 $14) 11. b3 c5 12. a5 $14)
10... cxd5 11. Bf4 Bb7 12. Bc7 $1 Qe8 13. Qb3 $1 (13. Nc3 $5 Nb8 (13... Rc8 14.
Nb5 Nc5 (14... a6 15. Na7 Ra8 16. Nc6 $16)) 14. Bf4 Nc6 15. Qd1) 13... Rc8 14.
Na3 $14 Ne4 (14... a6 $2 15. Bxb6) 15. Nb5 $14) (9... dxc4 $2 {is a clear
positional mistake. For example} 10. Qxc4 Nb6 11. Qb3 Bd7 12. Nc3 $16) (9...
Ne4 $6 {is a bit premature at this point!} 10. Be1 $14 (10. Be3 $5 $14 f5 11.
Nc3 $14) 10... f5 11. e3 Bd6 12. Nc3 a5 (12... g5 13. b4 $1 $14 (13. Ne2) 13...
g4 (13... Qf6 14. b5 $16 g4 15. Nd2) 14. Nh4 $3 Be7 15. b5 $3 Bxh4 16. gxh4 Rf7
(16... Qxh4 17. f3 $18 g3 18. hxg3 Nxg3 19. Qf2 f4 20. exf4) 17. bxc6 bxc6 18.
Nxe4 (18. Rab1) 18... fxe4 19. Rab1 $16 {black is too weak on the queenside!})
13. a3 g5 14. b4 $3 $16) (9... h6 10. b4 $1 $14 (10. e3 $14) 10... b6 11. a4) (
9... Re8 10. b4 $14 (10. e3 $14) (10. Bf4 $5 $14 Nh5 11. Be3 Nhf6 12. Nbd2 Ng4
13. Nf1 $1 Nxe3 14. Nxe3 $14)) 10. a3 $1 {An interesting waiting move - White
may soon play b4.} (10. e3 $5 {is also playable and good!} Ne4 (10... b6 {
After this, White demonstrates one advantage of e3:} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bf1 $1
Ba6 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. Nc3 Ra8 15. Nb5 Rc8 16. Qb3 $16 {Black has several weak
squares on the queenside!}) (10... h6 11. Be1 Re8 12. Nbd2 Bd6 13. Rd1 $1 $14)
11. Be1 f5 12. Nc3 g5 13. a3 $1 g4 14. Ne5 $14) 10... h6 $5 {appears to be a
usefull and typical waiting move} (10... b6 11. cxd5 $1 cxd5 12. Bf4 $1 {
White has very good play on the queenside! For a human, this position is
difficult to handle with the black pieces.} (12. Nc3 $5 {is also good.} Ba6 13.
Qb3 Ne4 14. Nb5 Nxd2 $2 15. Nxd2 Rc8 (15... Bxb5 $2 16. Qxb5 Rc8 17. e3 $16 {
Our bishop may come to f1, and White will continue to exploit Black's
weaknesses on the light squares.}) 16. Na7 $14 Rxc1+ 17. Rxc1 Qa8 18. Rc7 Qd8
19. Rc2 Bxe2 20. Rc8 Qxc8 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 22. Qe3 Rc1+ 23. Nf1 Rc2 24. Bxd5 Nf6
25. Be4 Rxb2 26. Qc3 Ra2 27. Bf3 Bxf3 28. Qxf3 Nd5 29. Qb3 Rxa3 30. Qb5 Ra1 31.
Kg2 Rd1 32. h4 g6 33. Nh2 h5 34. Nf3 Bf6 35. Qa4 Rd3 36. Qb5 Rd1 37. Qa4 Rd3
38. Qb5 Rd1 {½-½ (38) Niemann,H (2674)-Ganerdene,S (2418) Astana 2023}) 12...
Ba6 13. Nc3 Rc8 14. Qa4 $1 {White intends Nb5 and after} Rc4 {returns his
queen to d1.} (14... b5 15. Nxb5 Rxc1+ 16. Bxc1 Ne4 17. Na7 $5 (17. Qb3 Qb6 18.
a4 Rb8 19. Bf1 Ndf6 20. h3 Bxb5 21. Qxb5 Qxb5 22. axb5 Rxb5 23. e3 Rb8 24. Rxa5
Rc8 25. Ra1 g5 26. Ne1 h5 27. Be2 g4 28. hxg4 Nxg4 29. Nd3 f5 30. Bd1 Bd6 31.
f3 Bxg3 32. fxe4 dxe4 33. Nc5 e5 34. Bb3+ Kh8 35. Be6 Rd8 36. Bxf5 Bf2+ 37. Kg2
Bxe3 38. Bxg4 Bxd4 39. Ne6 {1-0 Karthik,V-Aczel,G/Prishtina KOS 2024})) 15. Qd1
$1 {Now the rook on c4 is exposed.} b5 (15... Qa8 16. e3 Rcc8 (16... Rfc8 $2
17. Nd2 R4c6 18. e4 dxe4 19. Ndxe4 $16) 17. Nd2 $1 (17. Bg5 $5 h6 18. Bxf6 Nxf6
19. Bf1 Bxf1 20. Qxf1 Qb7 21. Nb5 $14) 17... Rfd8 (17... h6 18. h4 Rfe8 19. g4
$14) (17... Qb7 18. e4 $16) 18. g4 $1 h6 19. h4 Nh7 20. Nf3 $36 Ndf8 21. Bg3
Qb7 22. Bf1 (22. Rab1) 22... Bxf1 23. Qxf1 $14) (15... Nh5 16. Bd2 f5 $2 {
Black pushes too hard...} 17. e3 Rc8 18. Qb3 (18. Ne2 $5) 18... Nhf6 19. Nb5
Ne4 20. Be1 $16 {White is solid on the kingside, while Black has created
several weaknesses. We can continue with either Bf1, or a4, etc.}) (15... Rc8
16. a4 $1 h6 17. Nb5 $1 Bxb5 18. axb5 $14) 16. e3 Qb6 17. Bf1 $14 {1-0 (59)
Carlsen,M (2830)-Firouzja,A (2738) Chess.com INT 2024}) (10... a4 $2 11. Bb4 $1
$16 b5 (11... Bxb4 $6 12. axb4 b5 13. c5 $1 Qe7 14. Nbd2 $16 e5 $2 15. e4 $1
$18) 12. c5 $14) (10... Ne4 $5 {This is what most people will play! Now, we
have ideas with b4! We also must never forget the resource 1...g4 2.Nh4! Our
king seems very safe in that case, while we will break through very fast on
the queenside!} 11. Be1 $14 Bd6 (11... f5 12. e3 Bd6 13. Nc3 g5 (13... Qe7 14.
Rab1 g5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 g4 17. Nh4 $16 Bxb4 $4 18. Rxb4 (18. Nxd5 cxd5 19.
Bxb4) 18... Qxb4 19. Nxe4 $18) 14. Ne2 g4 15. Nd2) 12. e3 f5 13. Nbd2 $14 (13.
Nc3 $5 Qe7 14. Ne2) 13... g5 14. b4 $3 g4 15. Nh4 Be7 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. b5 Bxh4
18. gxh4 Qxh4 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. cxd5 cxd5 21. Qc6 Ra6 22. Qc7 $16) 11. e3 $1 {
A move that is useful in any case in this system! We may play Nc3-Ne2!, or
even Bf1!, targeting the b5-square!} (11. Be1 $5 {is a good alternative. For
example} Ne4 12. Nc3 f5 13. e3 Bd6 14. b4 $1 axb4 15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Rxa1 Bxb4
17. Nxe4 Bxe1 (17... fxe4 18. Bxb4 $18) 18. Nd6 $1 Bb4 19. c5 $14 {White has
more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11... b6 (11... Ne4 12. Be1 Bd6
13. Nbd2 Nxd2 (13... f5 14. b4 $16) 14. Nxd2 Re8 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bc7 17.
Rd1 $16) 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bf1 Bb7 14. Nc3 Rc8 15. Qa4 $1 Ne4 16. Nb5 $1 $14 *

