1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. d4 c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Bf4
Nh5 9. Bd2 Nhf6 10. Rc1 Ne4 11. Be1 f5 12. e3 Bf6 13. a4 $3 {An amazing idea,
that works specifically at this point.} Qe7 (13... a5 {Since Black's bishop
has gone to f6, White can play} 14. b4 $3 axb4 15. Bxb4 c5 {This may look
attractive for Black, but after simply retreating the bishop, it turns out
that Black does not threaten anything!} 16. Be1 (16. Ba3 $16) 16... b6 17. cxd5
exd5 18. Nc3 Bb7 19. Rab1 $16 (19. dxc5 $5)) 14. a5 g5 15. Nc3 Nd6 16. b3 $5 (
16. c5 $6 Ne4) (16. cxd5 $1 exd5 17. a6 $1 $16 b6 $2 18. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 19. Qc6
Rb8 20. Bb4 $18) 16... dxc4 $2 17. bxc4 Nxc4 18. Ne2 $18 {The opening of the
queenside was in White's favour. Black's extra pawn does not play a role. I
strongly suggest that you study this game very carefully - you will learn a
lot!} b5 (18... Nd6 19. Bb4 $18 (19. a6 $5)) 19. axb6 Ndxb6 20. Qb3 c5 21. dxc5
Bxa1 22. cxb6 axb6 23. Nfd4 Bxd4 24. Nxd4 Na5 25. Qxb6 Ra6 26. Qb5 e5 27. Bxa5
exd4 28. Bb4 Qd7 29. Qc4+ Rf7 30. Qxc8+ Qxc8 31. Rxc8+ Kg7 32. exd4 Ra1+ 33.
Bf1 Rb7 34. Bc3 Rc1 35. d5+ Kg6 36. Rc6+ Kf7 37. Kg2 Rb3 38. Bd2 Rxc6 39. dxc6
Rb2 40. Bc4+ Kg6 41. c7 1-0

