1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Nbd7 4. d4 e6 5. c4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Qc2 c6 8. O-O
O-O 9. Rc1 Ne4 10. Be1 b6 {If Black wants to play with ...b6, then it would
have been best to play it without ...Ne4.} 11. Nc3 (11. Nbd2 $1 {was best; for
example} Nxd2 (11... f5 $2 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qc6 $18) 12. Nxd2 (12. Bxd2 $5)
12... Bb7 13. e4 $14) 11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Ba6 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e3 {Black is
close to equality, but he ended up clearly worse within a couple of moves.} Bd6
$6 15. Qa4 Bb7 $6 16. Bb4 $16 Bxb4 17. Qxb4 Rc8 18. Bf1 Nf6 19. Bd3 Rc7 20. Qe1
$1 {Very strong - White is taking control of the c-file.} Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Qd6 22.
Qc3 Rd8 23. Ne5 Ne8 24. Bxh7+ $1 {White increases his advantage by this
operation.} Kxh7 25. Nxf7 Qe7 26. Nxd8 Qxd8 27. Qa3 $18 {White has two pawns
and a rook for bishop and knight. Due to White's superior activity, he has a
decisive advantage.} Nd6 (27... a5 28. Qf8 $18) 28. Qxa7 Qe7 29. Qxb6 e5 30.
dxe5 Qxe5 31. Qd4 Qxd4 32. exd4 Nc4 33. b3 Nd2 34. Kg2 Ba6 35. f3 Be2 36. Rc2
Bxf3+ 37. Kf2 1-0

