1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8.
O-O dxc4 (8... Ne4 $6 {followed by ...f5 does not work here:} 9. Qc2 f5 10.
Nbd2 c6 11. b4 {Without dark-squared bishops this strategy is bound to fail.})
(8... b6 $6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Rac1 Ne4 12. Qc2 {White has a
positional advantage due to the weaknesses caused by ...b6.}) 9. a4 Qe7 10. Na3
e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxc4 Qe7 14. a5 $1 $14 {Black has freed his
position, yet White retains some positional advantage. 14.a5 is a great idea:
White threatens to play a6, and if Black plays ...a6 himself, his queenside
majority will be immobile.} a6 15. Rac1 Rd8 16. Qf4 Nd5 17. Qe5 Qxe5 18. Nxe5
c6 19. Rfd1 Be6 20. Nd3 $16 {The knight is transferred to c5 - White has
increased his advantage and went on to beat his high-level opponent.} Nc7 $2
21. Nc5 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rb8 23. Nxb7 $18 Bd5 24. Nc5 g6 25. e4 Be6 26. Rb1 Ba2
27. Ra1 Rxb2 28. Bf1 Bb1 29. f3 Kg7 30. Nxa6 Ne6 31. Ra3 Bc2 32. Rc3 Bd1 33.
Nc5 Nd4 34. f4 Nf3+ 35. Rxf3 Bxf3 36. a6 Ra2 37. h4 Bg4 38. e5 Bc8 39. Bd3 Ra5
40. Nb7 Ra3 41. Nc5 Rc3 42. a7 Ra3 43. Ba6 Rxa6 44. Nxa6 1-0

