1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nxd2 $1 {
With ...d5 already played, this is best. For example} O-O 7. Ngf3 b6 (7... c6
8. O-O b6 9. Qc2 {and White has a good version of the line 3...Bb4+ 4.Bd2 Bxd2
5.Qxd2 d5.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. O-O Bb7 10. Rc1 Nbd7 {In this structure, White
would prefer to have his knight on c3, but he is doing well anyway.} 11. Ne5 $1
$14 (11. Nb1 $5)) 6... b6 $6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nf3 Bb7 10. O-O $14 {
White has a small but clear positional advantage.} Nbd7 (10... Ne4 11. Qc2 Nd7
12. Rac1 $14) 11. Rac1 Qe7 12. Qf4 c6 {Black avoids going for Hanging Pawns
with ...c5, but after ...c6, the move e4 gains in strength.} 13. Rfe1 Qd8 14.
Nd2 Re8 15. e4 $1 {After some preparation, White goes for this thematic
advance.} Nf8 (15... dxe4 16. Ndxe4 $16 {White has a strong initiative.}) 16.
e5 $16 Ne6 17. Qe3 Ng4 18. Qd3 Nh6 19. Nf1 (19. f4 $1 $16) 19... a5 20. Ne3 g6
21. Na4 Rb8 22. a3 Kg7 23. f4 f5 24. exf6+ Qxf6 25. Nxb6 Qxd4 26. Qxd4+ Nxd4
27. Nd7 Rbd8 28. Ne5 Nf7 29. Nxd5 Nb3 30. Rc3 a4 31. Nb6 Rd2 32. Nxa4 Nd4 33.
Rce3 Ba8 34. Nc5 Rxb2 35. Ned3 Rxe3 36. Rxe3 Rb1+ 37. Re1 Rb5 38. a4 Ra5 39.
Re4 Nf5 40. g4 N5d6 41. Re7 Kf8 42. Rc7 Ne8 43. Ne6+ Kg8 44. Re7 Ned6 45. Ndc5
h5 46. g5 1-0

