1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 {In my opinion, this move order is
preferable over 4.Nf3, since it gives us the interesting option to play 4...
dxc4 5.Qa4+!?} (4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {With Nf3 instead of Bg2, White should
play the Catalan main lines with 5.Bg2. Since here, Black reaches comfortable
equality after} Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 7. Bg2 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 $11) 4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ $5
{This is an interesting idea, in connection with the move order 3.g3 d5 4.Bg2!}
(5. Nf3 {is the main line with tons of theory.}) 5... Nbd7 $1 (5... Bd7 $6 {
this natural-looking move leads to a passive position for Black!} 6. Qxc4 Bc6 (
6... Nc6 $6 7. Nf3 Na5 (7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 h6 (9... Qe7 10. Bg5 $16)
10. Rd1 Qe7 11. Qb3 $1 $14) 8. Qc3 $5 (8. Qd3 {also leads to a small advantage
for White.} c5 9. O-O Rc8 10. Nc3 cxd4 11. Nxd4 $14)) 7. Nf3 {Black solved the
problem of activating his light-squared bishop. To equalise fully, he would
like to play ...Bd5, followed by ...c5. However, this cannot be achieved
without concessions.} Bd5 (7... Nbd7 8. Nc3 $1 Be7 (8... Bd5 $2 9. Qd3 $5 (9.
Nxd5 exd5 10. Qb5 $16) 9... c5 $4 10. e4 $18) 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd3 $16 (10. Rd1
$16) (10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Rfe1 $14)) (7... Be7 8. O-O (8. Nc3 {
is possibly even more precise.}) 8... O-O 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {Black has no pawn
breaks! His position remains passive since he cannot activate the rooks.} 10.
Qd3 {White intends Rd1 and e4.} Re8 11. Rd1 (11. e4 $2 Nc5 $17 {- That's why
White needs to play Rd1 first!}) 11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 c6 $16) 8. Qa4+ $1 ({After
} 8. Qd3 Be4 9. Qd1 c5 10. Nc3 Bc6 11. O-O Nbd7 $14 {Black is close to
equality, though White is still slightly better.}) 8... Bc6 (8... Nbd7 9. Nc3
Bc6 10. Qc2 {White has an advantage. For example} Bb4 {(stopping, or at least
delaying e4)} 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 (13. Qxc3 Bd5 14. Bg5 h6 15.
Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Rac1 c6 17. a3 $14) 13... Be4 14. Qb3 $14) 9. Qd1 {Now Black no
longer attack White's queen.} Bb4+ (9... e5 $6 {may look interesting, but after
} 10. O-O $1 {White retains a big advantage due to his lead in development.}
exd4 (10... e4 11. Ne5 $18) 11. Nxd4 $1 (11. Qxd4 $5 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13.
Kxg2) 11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Bc5 13. Nf5 $16 (13. Nb3 Qxd1 $2 14. Rxd1 Bd6 15. Na5
$16)) 10. Bd2 (10. Nc3 $14) 10... Bxd2+ 11. Nbxd2 O-O 12. Qc2 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 c6
14. O-O $16) (5... c6 {is playable. White needs to know some accurate moves to
successfully fight against ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...c5.} 6. Qxc4 b5 (6... Nbd7 7.
Nf3 e5 $4 {This may look interesting but in fact it loses.} (7... Bd6 8. O-O
O-O 9. Nc3 $14 (9. Bf4 $5 {is also interesting - White gets solid control of
e5 after} Bxf4 10. gxf4 $14)) 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 (10. Qc3 $4 Bb4
$19) 10... Qxe5 11. Bxc6+ $1 $18) 7. Qd3 $1 {This is surprisingly the best
move! It is important to keep b5 under attack to make ...c5 more difficult to
achieve.} Bb7 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Be3 $3 $14 {This is best
- White fights against c5.} a6 (11... Nd5 $2 12. Nxd5 $16) 12. Ne4 $3 Nxe4 (
12... Nd5 13. Rac1 Nxe3 14. Qxe3) 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qd3 Nd5 15. Rfc1 $16) 6.
Qxc4 {And now there are two interesting moves for Black:  6...c5! and 6...a6!
6...c5 is best in my opinion, though Black has only a very narrow path to an
equal position if White plays the best moves.} c5 $1 (6... e5 $6 7. Nc3 $5 (7.
Nf3 $14) 7... exd4 8. Qxd4 Bc5 9. Qa4 $14 (9. Qf4 O-O 10. Nf3 Re8 11. O-O $14))
(6... a6 $1 7. Be3 $1 {Caruana's move - he used it to beat Anand (seemingly
easily!) in the 2018 Batumi Olympiad! I was playing just a few boards away
from them, and was shocked when I saw the move!} Bd6 {This was Anand's choice
- it's the most natural-looking move.} (7... Rb8 $5 8. Qc2 $5 (8. Nh3 $1 b5 9.
Qc2 Bb7 10. Bxb7 Rxb7 11. O-O Bd6 {White has a nice, small advantage after
both 12.Nd2! and 12.Nc3!} (11... Nd5 12. Bg5) 12. Nc3 (12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nb3 $14
(13. Ne4 $14)) 12... O-O 13. Ne4 $14) 8... Bd6 (8... b5 9. Nh3 $3 Bb7 10. Bxb7
Rxb7 11. O-O Bd6 12. Nd2 O-O (12... Nd5 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bf4 $3 Nxf4 15. Nxf4
Bxf4 16. gxf4 O-O 17. Ne4 $16) 13. Nb3 $14) 9. Nh3 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Nc3 Bb7
12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Rfd1 Qa8 14. Ng5 $1 (14. d5 $5 $14) 14... h6 15. Nge4 $14) (
7... Nb6 $2 {abandoning the control of the important central squares e5 and c5!
} 8. Qb3 $5 $14 (8. Qc1 $5 $14) (8. Qd3 $5 $14 Nbd5 9. Nf3 Nxe3 10. Qxe3 c5 11.
Nc3 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Nb3 Bb4 15. Rc1 Ke7 16. O-O Rb8 17. Ne4
Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Rd8 19. Rc7+ Rd7 20. Rc4 Bd6 21. Rfc1 Rd8 22. Na5 f5 23. Bg2 e5
24. Bd5 e4 25. f3 Bxg3 26. fxe4 Be5 27. Rb4 fxe4 28. Bxe4 Rd4 29. Rcc4 {
1/2-1/2 Gleizerov,E-Beerdsen,T/Groningen NED 2019/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 8... Nbd5 9. Nf3
{White is prepared to give up his dark-squared bishop. He will be ahead in
development and it will not be easy for Black to activate his light-squared
bishop.} Nxe3 (9... c5 10. O-O (10. dxc5 $14 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+
13. Nbxd2 Bxc5 14. Rc1 $16) 10... Nxe3 11. Qxe3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bc5 13. Nxe6 $1
$16) 10. Qxe3 Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rd1 $14 (12. Nc3 Nd5 13. Qd2 $14)) (7... Ng4
$6 {Not a good move, but a tricky one! WE MUST REMEMBER 9.dc5!} 8. Bd2 $1 (8.
Qc1 $5 {is also interesting.} c5 9. Nf3 Nxe3 10. Qxe3 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Be7 $1 12.
Nc3 O-O (12... Nf6 13. Qe3 $14 (13. Qxd8+ $14)) (12... Bf6 13. Qf4 $1) 13. O-O
Bf6 14. Qf4 $1 $14 (14. Qe3 Qb6 $36)) 8... c5 9. dxc5 $1 ({But not} 9. Nf3 $2
b5 $15 {with a good game for Black, 0-1 (29) Kantorik,M-Raja,R/Teplice CZE 2023
}) 9... Nge5 10. Qc2 Bxc5 (10... Nxc5 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Be7 13. O-O O-O
14. Be3 $16) 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Qc7 {As long as we don't blunder our queen,
White is much better since Black has problems developing his queenside.} 13.
Na3 $1 (13. O-O $4 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Qxc2) (13. Nc3 Ne5 14. Bg2 O-O 15. O-O $16
Nc6 16. Rac1 Nd4 17. Qe4 $3 $16) 13... O-O 14. b4 Bd6 15. Qxc7 Bxc7 16. Rc1 $16
) (7... Be7 $1 {SUPER SOS! A VERY TRICKY LINE! WE NEED TO KNOW THE AMAZING 8.
Qc1!! += Remember the rule: WHEN WE SEE BLACK DEVELOP WITH ...Be7, WE DEVELOP
OUR KNIGHT TO f3!} 8. Qc1 $3 {the queen will end up on e3 in many cases ! The
queen protects the bishop, while stepping out of ...b5, coming with tempo!
This is White's only good move here, and we must remember it!} (8. Nh3 $6 O-O
9. O-O Nd5 10. Nc3 $2 Nxe3 $17 {0-1 (56) Menezes,C-Zwardon,V/Czech Republic
CZE 2023/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) (8. Nf3 $6 b5 $1 9. Qd3 (9. Qc6 Rb8 $132) 9... Bb7 $132)
(8. Nd2 $6 Nb6 9. Qb3 Nfd5 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Ngf3 Nxe3 12. Qxe3 Nd5 13. Qb3 b6
