1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 ({We already covered} 4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {
under the move order 3...Bb4+ 4.Bd2 Be7.} a5 (5... Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O c6 8.
Qc2 Nbd7 9. Rc1 $5) 6. Qa4+ $5 Bd7 7. Qc2) (4... c5 5. Nf3 $5 (5. cxd5 $5 exd5
6. Nf3 {transposes to the Tarrasch Defence!}) 5... Nc6 (5... dxc4 6. O-O Nc6 7.
dxc5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Ne1 $5 $14 (11. Nb3 Be7 12.
c4 Bd7 13. Bb2 Rfd8 14. Nfd4 (14. Ne5 $14) 14... Rac8 15. Nb5 $14)) 6. O-O cxd4
$2 (6... dxc4 7. dxc5 {see 5...dxc4.}) 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Nb3 Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10.
Nc3 Be6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Rc1 $16) 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 $1 (7... b5
$5 {This was very fashionable for some time, though White can get a small plus
without too much effort!} 8. a4 $1 b4 (8... Bb7 9. axb5 a6 $5 {Black gives up
a pawn and achieves a simplified position with considerable drawing chances.
White has a few ways to get a risk-free advantage.} 10. bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qxc4 Bd5
12. Qc3 $1 c5 (12... Ne4 13. Qe3 c5 14. Nc3 $1 $14) 13. Be3 $1 Ne4 14. Qe1 $1
Nb4 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Nc3 Nxc3 (16... Nc2 17. Nxd5 $1 (17. Qc1 Nxe3 18. fxe3
$14) 17... Nxe1 18. Nxe7+ Kh8 19. Rxe1 $18 Qe8 20. Ne5 $18) 17. bxc3 Nc2 18.
Qd2 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 cxd4 20. cxd4 Rd8 21. Qf4 $3 h6 22. e3 Bd6 23. Qh4 $3 Bb4 24.
Qg4 $3 $16 {IT IS GOOD IF YOU KNOW THE LINE UP TO HERE! See model game
So-Nepomniachtchi.}) 9. Nbd2 $1 {This is a simple and interesting alternative
to 9.Nbd2 - with much less theory! Study the most important ideas and model
games!} Bb7 10. Nxc4 Be4 (10... Nbd7 11. Nfe5 $5 (11. Rd1 $5 $14) (11. Bg5 $5)
11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Rd1 $16 Qc8 15. Be3 Nb6 (15... Qb7+)
16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. Qe4 $16) 11. Qd1 $1 {is equally good as 11.Qb3.} (11. Qb3 $1
Nc6 (11... c5 12. Be3 $1 (12. dxc5 $1 $14) 12... Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14. dxc5 $14
Nxc5 15. Bxc5 Bxc5 16. Nfe5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qb7+ 18. Qf3 $16) (11... Nbd7 12. Rd1
$14 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Rfd1 Qd5 15. Rac1 Rfd8 16. Ncd2 $3 $16) (12.
Be3 $1 $14 {The bishop stands in fact perfectly on e3, ready to be exchanged
on c5, while we also do not mind exchanging it for the f6-knight!} Nd5 13. Rfd1
Nxe3 14. Qxe3 $16) 12... c5 13. Nfe5 (13. Be3 $5 $14)) 12. Rd1 Qd5 (12... h6
13. Be3 $16 Nd5 14. Nfe5 $16 (14. Rac1)) 13. a5 (13. Be3 $3 Rfd8 14. Ne1 $3 {
SOS! Remember this great plan: Bf3, Ne1!, threatening f3!-Bf2-e4!} Bxg2 (14...
Rac8 $2 15. f3 $1 Bg6 16. Bf2 $1 $16) (14... a5 $2 15. f3 Bg6 16. Bf2 $18) 15.
Nxg2 Na5 (15... h6 16. f3 $1 Rac8 17. Bf2 a5 $2 18. e4 Qd7 19. Rac1 $16) (15...
a5 16. f3) 16. Nxa5 Qxa5 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. Nf4 $14) 13... Ne8 14. Bf4 Nd6 15.
Ncd2 Nxd4 16. Qxd5 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bxd5 18. e4 e5 19. Bxe5 Be6 20. Rac1 Rac8 21.
Bd4 Nb5 22. Be3 c5 23. Be2 Nd4 24. Bxd4 cxd4 25. Nf3 h6 26. Nxd4 Rxc1 27. Rxc1
Bf6 28. Nxe6 fxe6 29. Bg4 Bxb2 30. Bxe6+ Kh8 31. Rc4 Bc3 {1-0 Xiao,Y-Nicolas
Zapata,I/Maribor SLO 2012/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 11... c5 (11... Nbd7 12. Nfe5 $3 $16 (
12. Bg5 $5 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rc1 $14) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nxe5 (13... c5 14.
Nc6 Qe8 15. Bg5 $14) 14. dxe5 $3 Nd7 (14... Qd5+ 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. e4 Nb6 17.
Na5 $16) 15. e4 $1 (15. Be3 $14) 15... Nc5 16. Be3 (16. Na5 $16) 16... Nxe4 17.
Rc1 $16 {0-1 Zhao Jun-Vusatiuk,V/chess.com INT 2022/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 12. dxc5 Na6 (
12... Bxc5 13. Nfe5 Bxg2 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Kxg2 Nbd7 16. Nd3 $16) (12... Nbd7
13. Be3 Nxc5 14. Bxc5 Bxc5 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Rfc1 $14) 13. Qxd8 $3 Rfxd8 14.
Nfe5 Bxc5 15. Bg5 Rd4 16. Rac1 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Ne4 18. Bf4 Bf8 19. Be3 Rd5 20.
Nd3 Nec5 21. Bxc5 Bxc5 22. Nd2 Rad8 23. Nb3 Be7 24. Rc6 R5d6 25. Rfc1 g6 26.
Na5 Bf6 27. Nb7 Rxc6 28. Rxc6 Rd7 29. Nd6 Nb8 30. Ne4 Kg7 31. Rc8 Rd8 32. Rxd8
Bxd8 33. Nxb4 a5 34. Nd3 Nc6 35. Nd6 f5 36. f4 Be7 37. Nc4 g5 38. Nde5 Nxe5 39.
Nxe5 gxf4 40. Nc6 Bf6 41. Nxa5 Kf7 42. gxf4 Bxb2 43. Nc4 Bd4 44. Ne5+ Ke8 45.
a5 Bxe5 46. fxe5 Kd7 {1-0 Lafuente,P-Gurevich,D/Toluca 2011/CBM 141 Extra/[,
ÃéÜííçò]}) (7... b6 {This is another playable line.} 8. Bg5 $5 (8. Qxc4 $5)
8... Nd5 $1 (8... Bb7 $4 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ng5 $1 $18) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbd2 $5
(10. Qxc4 Ba6 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. Nc3 $14 Nxc3 13. bxc3) 10... b5 (10... Bb7 11.
Nxc4 Nd7 12. Rfd1 (12. Rac1 c5 13. Rfd1 Rac8 14. Qa4 a6 15. Qa3 $14) 12... c5
13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. a3 $1 Rac8 15. Rac1 $14) 11. b3 c3 (11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 $14 {
with very good, typical Catalan compensation!}) 12. e4 cxd2 13. exd5 exd5 14.
Qxd2 Be6 15. Rac1 c6 16. Ne5 $14 {again with good compensation.} (16. Rfe1 $14)
) ({After} 7... Bd7 $6 8. Qxc4 (8. Ne5 $5) 8... Bc6 {Black has a worse version
of the line 7...a6 8.a4 Bd7.} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Qd3 $14 {We will continue with
Rd1 and e4.}) 8. a4 $1 {This is the move I recommend - 8.Qxc4 is the
alternative.} Bd7 $1 (8... c5 $6 9. dxc5 Qd5 (9... Bxc5 10. Nbd2 $1 Nc6 11.
Nxc4 Qe7 12. Nfe5 $3 Nd4 13. Qd1 Rd8 14. Bd2 $16 (14. e3 $16))) (8... Nc6 $5 {
is another playable move against which we should know how to react! I suggest
a move that is very rare, yet very simple and good - 10.Na3! instead of 10.
Nbd2.} 9. Qxc4 Qd5 $1 (9... Bd7 $2 10. Bd2 $3 {A great move, stopping any ...
Na5 ideas!} h6 11. Rd1 $16 (11. Nc3 $6 Na5 12. Qa2 Bc6 $132) (11. Na3 $5 $16))
10. Na3 $5 {Rare but good!} (10. Nbd2 {is the main move.}) 10... Rd8 (10...
Bxa3 11. Qxd5 exd5 12. Rxa3 Bf5 13. Bf4 Rfc8 14. Rc1 $16) (10... Qxc4 $2 11.
Nxc4 Rd8 12. e3 $16) 11. Be3 Qh5 (11... Ng4 12. Bf4 $16) (11... Bd7 12. Qc1 $14
(12. Bd2 $5 {(stopping ...Na5 )} Be8 13. e3 $14)) 12. h3 $1 e5 $6 (12... Nd5
13. Bd2 $14) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 $16 Qxb2 16. Rfb1 Qd4 17. Qxc7
Rd7 18. Qc4 $18) 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 $1 {This is simple and as good as 10.Bg5!
This line has very nice characteristics that I like very much - not many
forced lines, and easy to play with White!} (10. Nc3 $2 {This is a mistake !}
b5 11. Qd3 b4 12. Nb1 Be4 13. Qd1 c5 $15) 10... Bd6 $5 (10... Nd5 11. Bd2 (11.
Qc1 Nxf4 12. Qxf4 Nd7 (12... a5 13. Nc3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. e3 Na6 16. h4 g6
17. h5 $14) 13. Nc3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $14) (11. Nc3 $5 Nxf4 12. gxf4 Nd7 13. e3 a5
14. Rfd1 $14 {see model game 1-0 (40) Papaioannou,I (2577)-Iordachescu,V (2601)
Turin 2006.}) 11... a5 (11... Bb5 $2 {This looks like a clever trick, but it
turns out to be a mistake:} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Qxd5 $1 Qxd5 14. Rxa8 Nc6 15. Ne5
$18 {White has too much material for the queen.} (15. Nc3 $16)) 12. Nc3 $14) (
10... a5 {is another common idea - creating an outpost on b4 for Black's
pieces.} 11. Nc3 Na6 (11... Nd5 $6 12. Nxd5 (12. Bd2 $5) (12. Rac1 {can also
be considered.} Nxf4 13. gxf4 {followed by e3, Kh1, Rg1, Ne5.}) 12... exd5 13.
Qc3 $1 {If Qc2, then ...Na6-b4 would come with a tempo. We don't mind} Bb4 14.
Qc2 $14) 12. Rac1 $5 (12. Ne5 $5) (12. Rfd1 $5) 12... Nb4 (12... h6 13. Rfe1
$14) (12... Bd6 {If Black wants to play this, he should do so earlier.} 13. Bg5
$1 {With the knight on a6, this gains in strength.} h6 (13... Bd5 $2 14. Nxd5
exd5 15. Bxf6 dxc4 16. Bxd8 Raxd8 17. Rxc4 $18) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e4 Qe7 16.
Nh4 $3 Bb4 17. f4 $14) 13. Ne5 $1 {This is part of White's plan. Black's
pieces are targeting e4 and d5 - with Ne5 White takes these squares under
control. For example} Bxg2 14. Kxg2 c6 15. e4 Nd7 (15... Qb6 16. Rfd1 Qa6 17.
Qb3 $14 ({Even} 17. Qxa6 Rxa6 18. g4 $14 {would give a small advantage.})) 16.
Nf3 $3 {Since White has more space we should not make Black's life easier by
exchanging pieces.} Nb6 17. Qe2 $16) (10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 a5 12. Rfd1 $14 (12.
Qd3 $14)) 11. Qc1 $5 {This is maybe best, although Bg5 is very interesting as
well! From now on, not much concrete theory is needed!} (11. Bg5 $5 Nbd7 12.
Nc3 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Rfe1 $14 {Sometimes the computer calls these
positions equal, but in practical play, White is always slightly better!} (14.
Rfd1 $14) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 16. h4 a5 17. h5 $14) 11... a5 (11... Bxf4 $6
12. Qxf4 Qd6 (12... Nbd7 13. Nc3 Nd5 14. Qd2 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Nf6 16. Rfd1 Bxf3 (
16... Qe7 17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Nd5 19. Qb3 c6 20. Nd3 a5 21. e3 $14) 17. Bxf3
c6 18. b4 $14 (18. e3 a5 19. b4 axb4 20. Qxb4 Ra7 21. a5 Nd5 22. Qc5 $14)) 13.
Rc1 $14 (13. Nc3 Qxf4 14. gxf4 a5 (14... Bxf3 $6 15. Bxf3 c6 16. a5 $16) 15.
Ne5 $14)) (11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 $14) (11... Nd5 12. Bg5 Nf6 (12... f6 13. Bd2 f5
14. Nc3 $14) 13. Nc3 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qc2 $14 (15. e4)) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Rd1
$14 (13. Bg5 $5) 13... h6 (13... Nd5 14. Bd2 Nab4 15. e4 Nb6 16. Be3 $14) 14.
Bd2 $5 (14. Be5 $5 Bxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 c6 17. Nc4 Nb4 18. e4 $14) 14...
Nb4 (14... Bb4 15. Qc2 $14) 15. Qb1 $1 Nbd5 (15... b6 16. e4 $16) 16. Nh4 $5
Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Bxg2 18. Nxg2 $14 *

