1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. d4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4
Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 Bd6 11. Bg5 Nbd7 (11... a5 $6 12. Nc3 h6 (12... Nbd7 $2
13. e4) 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. e4 Qe7 15. Qe2 $14) 12. Nc3 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Rfd1
Bd5 15. Qd3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6 {In such positions White should try to put his
pawn on h5. Another good plan is to put the knight on c4.} 17. e4 {In my
opinion this is premature - after e4, White must always watch out for ...e5,
which would have been a good move:} (17. a5 $2 Bb4 $15) (17. Nb1 $5 {[%cal
Yb1d2,Yd2c4,Yb1a3,Ya3c4]}) (17. h4 $5) 17... Bb4 (17... e5 $1 18. d5 Rc8 $1
$132 (18... c5 $2 19. Be2 $16)) 18. Na2 (18. e5 $5 Nd5 19. h4 Rc8 20. h5 Qa5
21. Nxd5 (21. Ne2 $5 $14) (21. Rdc1) 21... cxd5 22. Be2 $14 {Even in this
simplified position, Black has to be careful - once White is able to install a
battery on the b1-h7 diagonal, Black is in big trouble.}) (18. h4 $5) 18... Be7
19. Qb3 Rb8 20. Rac1 Qa5 21. d5 exd5 22. exd5 cxd5 (22... Nxd5 $5 $11) 23. Nc3
$5 b5 (23... Qb4 $11) 24. axb5 axb5 25. Nxd5 Nxd5 26. Bxd5 Bf6 27. Bxf7+ Rxf7
28. Rd7 Rbf8 29. Qe6 b4 30. Rcc7 Qe5 31. Qc4 Qe1+ 32. Kg2 Be7 33. Rxe7 1/2-1/2

