{This game clearly demonstrates that it's not about concrete theory, but about
understanding the arising position! White managed to get a good knight against
a bad dark-squared bishop - a strategy very similar to the Nd3 type of
positions!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7.
Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 Nd5 11. Nc3 Nxf4 (11... Nd7 12. Nxd5 exd5
13. Qc3 $14) 12. gxf4 Nd7 (12... a5 13. Ne5 $14) 13. e3 a5 14. Rfd1 Nf6 (14...
Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 16. Kh1 Nf6 17. Rg1 Nd5 18. Ne4 {White will continue by
doubling on the g-file.}) 15. Qb3 Rb8 (15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Rb8 17. d5 exd5 18.
Nxd5 $14) 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 c6 18. Rac1 $14 Bb4 (18... Nd7 19. Nd3 $14) 19.
Kh1 Re8 (19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 {I had evaluated the following endgame in my
favour.} (20. Qxc3 Qd5+ 21. f3 {was possible as well.}) 20... Qd5+ 21. Qxd5
cxd5 22. c4 dxc4 23. Rxc4 $14) 20. Rg1 Bf8 (20... g6 21. f5) 21. Rg2 Re7 22.
Rcg1 Rc8 23. Qd1 c5 24. dxc5 {I was happy to play the following endgame! My
idea was to scare my opponent with an attack and provoke him to exchange
queens.} Qxd1 25. Rxd1 Rxc5 26. Rgg1 Rc8 27. Rd3 $1 {White's long-term plan is
Nb5-b3-Nc4!, when Black's dark-squared bishop lacks potential!} g6 28. Rgd1
Rec7 29. Kg2 Be7 30. Kf3 {Centralising the king and controlling e4.} Kf8 31.
Nb5 $1 Rc1 32. b3 $1 $16 Rxd1 33. Rxd1 Ke8 $2 (33... Rd8 $2 34. Rxd8+ Bxd8 35.
Nd6 $18) (33... Nd5 34. Nc4 Bb4 35. Rd3) 34. Nc4 $18 Rb8 35. Nxa5 Nd5 36. Nc4
Bc5 37. e4 Nb4 38. Ne5 Rc8 39. Rd7 f6 40. Nc7+ 1-0

