1. d4 e6 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4
Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 a5 11. Nc3 Na6 12. Rac1 Nb4 (12... Bd6 13. Bg5 $1 {
After ...Na6, this gains in strength - Black would like to have his pawn on d7
in this case.} h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e4 Qe7 16. Rfe1 (16. Nh4 $1) 16... Nb4 17.
Nb5 {We know that e5 wins, but I want to show that after} (17. e5 $18) 17...
Bxb5 18. axb5 $14 {White is also better.}) 13. Rfd1 h6 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c6
(15... Nfd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bd2 $14 c6 18. e4 Nb4 19. Bxb4 (19. Bf4 $14)
19... Bxb4 20. h4 Bd6 21. Nf3 Qe7 22. h5 $14) 16. e4 $16 Qb6 (16... Nh5 $6 17.
Be3 $16) (16... Nd7 17. Nf3 $1 $16 (17. Nxd7 Qxd7 {is also better for White,
but Black's situation has improved.} 18. d5 exd5 19. exd5 cxd5 $6 20. Nxd5 Nxd5
21. Qxd5 (21. Rxd5 $16) 21... Qxd5+ (21... Qxa4 $11) 22. Rxd5 $16 {An ending
like this is much better for White - Black's queenside pawns are weak, and
White's rooks are ready to enter on the 6th or 7th rank. Most likely, we will
end up with an extra pawn; for example} Bb4 23. Rc7 b6 24. Be3 Bc5 25. Bxc5
bxc5 26. Rcxc5 Rfb8 27. Rb5 $1 $18 (27. Rxa5 Rxa5 28. Rxa5 Rxb2 29. Rb5 $1 (29.
h4 $5 Ra2 30. h5) 29... Ra2 30. a5 $16))) 17. Qe2 Qa6 (17... Rfd8 18. Be3 $16)
18. Qf3 $16 (18. Nc4 $1 $16) (18. Qxa6 $14 {is also better for White, but
slightly less so than the alternatives.}) 18... Rad8 19. b3 (19. h4 $5 Nd7 20.
Ng4 $14) 19... Qa7 20. Be3 Qa6 21. h4 Nd7 22. Nc4 Nf6 $2 (22... b5 $1 23. Nb2
$1 $14 (23. axb5 $2 cxb5 24. Na3 Na2 $1 25. Nxa2 Bxa3 $132)) 23. g4 $1 Nh7 (
23... Nd7 24. g5 $18) 24. g5 $1 $18 g6 25. e5 h5 26. Ne4 Rfe8 27. Nf6+ Nxf6 28.
gxf6 Bf8 29. Kh2 Kh7 30. Rg1 c5 31. Rg5 1-0

