1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O c6 $1 {This is a
different line than 6...Nbd7. After 6...c6 Black wants to continue with ...b6
first, and only then decide where to develop his his bishop and knight!} (6...
Nc6 $2 {The knight is misplaced on c6.} 7. b3 $16 (7. Nbd2 $16)) (6... Nbd7 7.
Qc2 $1 {After 6...Nbd7, the plan with Qc2!-Nbd2-e4! is working perfectly!} (7.
Nbd2 $6 c5 (7... b6 $1 8. cxd5 exd5 {In this structure, the d2-knight is
misplaced - it very much would prefer to be on c3!}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. dxc5 Nxc5
10. Nb3 Nce4) 7... c6 (7... b6 $6 8. cxd5 $1 exd5 9. Qc6 $16 (9. Nc3 Bb7 10.
Bf4 $14) 9... Ba6 10. Nc3 Rc8 11. Qa4 $16) 8. Nbd2 $1 b6 (8... b5 $2 {Here,
and in similar positions ...b5 is a strategic mistake. White plays the tyical
move} 9. c5 $1 {with a big advantage. For example} a5 10. e4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4
12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qc2 Nd5 14. Bd2 Bb7 15. Rfe1 $16) 9. e4 {This line was
popular for Black in the past - now it has been proven that White gets a
significant advantage.} Bb7 {Black wants to keep the game more complicated,
however, White now gets a significant space advantage.} (9... Nxe4 {After this,
White easily gets an advantage.} 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4 Bb7 12. Rd1 Nf6 13. Qe2
$1 (13. Qc2 $1 Qc8 14. c5 $3 Nd5 15. Bg5 $16) 13... Qc8 14. Bf4 $16) (9... Ba6
$6 {The bishop will turn out to be misplaced on a6.} 10. b3 $1 Rc8 (10... dxe4
11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 b5 13. c5 $16) 11. Bb2 c5 (11... b5 $2 12. e5 Ne8 13. c5
$18) 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rfd1 {White is better prepared for the opening of the
position - his pieces are more active.} (13. Rfe1 dxc4 14. bxc4 $3 cxd4 15.
Nxd4 $16) 13... cxd4 (13... dxc4 14. bxc4 $1 (14. Nxc4 $5 b5 15. Nce5 cxd4 16.
Nc6 $1 $18 (16. Qf5 $16)) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 $16) 14. Nxd4 Re8 15. Qf5 $3 (15.
Nf5 $14) 15... g6 16. Qg5 $1 $16) 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Re1 $1 {
Stopping any ...f7-f6 ideas and vacating f1 for our bishop or knight! White
will regroup his pieces and prepare an attack on the kingside. For example:}
Rc8 13. Qd1 $1 (13. Qa4 $1 Bc6 (13... a6 14. Bf1 b5 15. Qd1 Nb6 16. Bd3 Nc4 17.
h4 $16 (17. Nf1)) 14. Qd1 a5 15. Bf1 Nc7 16. Bd3 Bb5 17. Bb1 $1 {It's best to
keep the attacking bishop.} Re8 18. h4 Nf8 19. Nf1 $16) 13... Qc7 (13... Ba6
14. Nf1 Nb8 15. h4 Nc6 16. a3 $16 (16. Bg5 $16)) (13... a5 14. Bf1 Nc7 15. Bd3
Ba6 16. Bb1 Re8 17. h4 $16) (13... Ba6 14. Nf1 (14. Nb1 b5 15. a3 $16) 14...
Qc7 15. Ne3 $16) 14. Nb1 $1 {White improves the knight and prevents ...Qc2.} b5
(14... Qc2 $2 15. Qxc2 Rxc2 16. Nc3 f6 17. Bh3 $16) (14... Ba6 15. Nc3 Nb8 16.
h4 $16) 15. Bf1 $1 $16 (15. a3 $1 b4 16. axb4 Bxb4 17. Bd2 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 (18.
Nbxd2 $16) 18... a6 19. Nc3 $16) 15... b4 16. Bd3 h6 (16... Qb6 17. a4 $3 (17.
Bg5 $14) 17... bxa3 18. Nxa3 $16) 17. Bf4 Qb6 18. Nbd2 Ba6 19. Bc2 f5 (19...
Nc7 20. Nb3 Nb5 (20... Bc4 21. Qd2 $16) 21. Bb1 $18 (21. Qd3)) (19... Bb5 20.
Rc1 a5 (20... Rc6 21. Bb1 $16) 21. Bh7+ $18) 20. exf6 Rxf6 21. Rc1 Nd6 22. Ne5
Nf8 23. Ndf3 Nc4 24. b3 Na3 25. Ng4 Rf7 26. Nfe5 $18 {1-0 (32) Gelfand,B (2729)
-Stupak,K (2573) Tbilisi 2017}) (6... b6 $2 7. cxd5 exd5 (7... Nxd5 8. e4 Nf6
9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Re1 c5 11. d5 $1 exd5 12. exd5 $16 Nxd5 $2 13. Ne5 Nxc3 14. Qxd8
Rxd8 15. Bxb7 $18) 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Ne5 $1 Nbd7 10. Qa4 $1 $16) 7. Qc2 $5 {
This is playable and good - but ONLY if we are accurate with the move order!} (
7. Nc3 {is another good move - it was analysed in my previous lectures on the
Catalan.}) 7... b6 $1 (7... b5 $2 8. c5 $16) (7... Nbd7 $6 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 {
transposes to 6...Nbd7.}) (7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3 $1 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11.
Be3 $1 a6 12. Ne4 $1 $14) 8. Rd1 $1 {The most accurate continuation. White
plays a useful move, waiting for Black to show his hand. As a general rule: If
Black continues with ...Bb7, we develop with Nc3, while if Black continues
with ...Ba6, we develop with Nbd2.} (8. Nbd2 $6 {This is good against 6...Nbd7,
while here Black gets good counterplay after} c5 $1 {Black immediately gets
active, exploiting the passive position of the d2-knight.} ({or} 8... Bb7 $5 9.
e4 Na6 $1 $132) 9. cxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. e4 Nc6 $1 12. exd5 Nb4 $132)
8... Bb7 (8... Ba6 9. b3 $1 {I prefer this move, though Ne5 is also good:} (9.
Ne5 $5 Qc8 (9... Nfd7 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e4 Nxe5 12. exd5 $3) 10. b3 Nbd7 11.
Ba3 $14 (11. Bb2 $14)) 9... Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Rc8 (10... c5 $5 {An interesting
attempt to avoid ...Rc8 !} 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Rac1 cxd4 (12... dxc4 $6 13. Nxc4
$14 b5 $2 14. Nce5 cxd4 15. Nc6 Qe8 16. Nfxd4 Bc5 17. Qd3 $18) (12... Qc7 13.
dxc5 $3 Bxc5 (13... bxc5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. e4 $16) 14. Qb1 $16 Qb8 15. cxd5
exd5 16. e3) (12... b5 13. cxb5 Bxb5 14. e4 $14) 13. Nxd4 b5 14. Qb1 bxc4 15.
bxc4 Qb6 (15... dxc4 16. Nc6 $18) 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Nf5 $14) 11.
e4 c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 Bb7 (13... dxc4 14. bxc4 $1) (13... Re8 14. Rac1 (
14. Nf1 $14) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 b5 16. Qb1 $14 (16. Nf5 $14) 16... bxc4 17.
bxc4 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Rxc4 19. Nc6 $14) 14. Nf1 $14 dxc4 $2 15. d5 $3 Bxd5 (15...
c3 16. Qxc3 $16) 16. Ng5 $1 $18 Bxg2 17. Bxf6 Be4 18. Qxe4 Nxf6 19. Rxd8 Nxe4
20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 21. Nxe4 $18) 9. Nc3 $1 (9. Nbd2 $6 {is again inferior due to}
c5 $132) 9... Nbd7 (9... dxc4 10. Ne5 Qc8 (10... b5 11. Nxb5) 11. Bg5 $3 (11.
Nxc4 c5 $14) 11... b5 12. Ne4 Nbd7 13. b3 cxb3 14. axb3 $16) 10. b3 $1 {
With this, we prepare e4. If e4 now, the Black could have taken on c4.} Ba6 $1
{This is pretty much Black's only acceptable move.} (10... c5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12.
Nxd5 Bxd5 13. e4 Bb7 14. Bb2 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Rc8 16. Qe2 $16) (10... Rc8 11. e4
$1 c5 $2 (11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Qc7 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16.
c5 $3 Qc7 (16... bxc5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 $4 18. Qb4 Qe7 19. Rdc1 Rfd8 20. Rxc5 $18 (
20. Qxc5 $4 Rd1+ $19)) 17. b4 Nf6 18. Qe1 $1 $16) 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 $3 dxc4
(13... Qc7 14. Nxd5 $3 $16 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. dxc5 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qxc5 (
17... Nxc5 18. Bd5 Nd7 19. Qf5 $18) 18. Qe2 Bf6 19. Rac1 Rce8 20. Qxe8 Rxe8 21.
Rxc5 Nxc5 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. b4 Na6 24. a3 Nb8 25. Rc1 $18) 14. d5 $3 Bd6 (14...
cxb3 15. axb3 $16) 15. bxc4 $16) 11. Qd3 $1 {With this move, we transpose to
another well-known theoretical variation. Here, both sides have lost a tempo -
Black by playing ...Bb7-Ba6, and White by playing Qc2-Qd3.} (11. Bf4 $1 {
is also natural and good!} Nh5 (11... dxc4 $2 12. bxc4 Bxc4 13. Nd2 Ba6 14.
Bxc6 Rc8 15. Qa4 Nh5 16. Be5 $1 $16) (11... Rc8 12. e4 $3 dxc4 13. Nd2 $1 b5 (
13... Nh5 14. Be3 Nhf6 15. Nxc4 $14) 14. bxc4 bxc4 15. Bf1 Nb6 16. a4 $16) 12.
Be3 (12. Bc1 Nhf6 $11) 12... Rc8 (12... Nhf6 13. Na4 $5) 13. a4 $3 Nhf6 14. a5
$14) 11... c5 (11... Bb4 $2 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Ne4 14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Bf4 $16 (
15. a4 $16)) (11... Rc8 12. e4 $14 (12. Bb2 $14 c5 13. Nb5) 12... b5 13. cxd5
cxd5 14. e5 Ne8 15. Nxb5 $16 Nc7 16. a4 Rb8 17. Qe3 Bxb5 18. axb5 Nxb5 19. Bf1
$16) (11... Qc8 $5 {is also interesting!} 12. a4 $1 (12. Bf4 c5 13. Rac1 dxc4
14. bxc4 cxd4 15. Nb5 $14) 12... c5 (12... Bb4 13. Bb2 $14 (13. Ba3 $14)) 13.
Ba3 $1 Re8 (13... Rd8 14. e4 dxc4 15. bxc4 $16) 14. Ne5 $14) 12. Bb2 (12. dxc5
Bxc5 $1 13. Qc2 $132) 12... Rc8 (12... Qc7 13. Nb5 Bxb5 14. cxb5 Qb7 15. e3 $14
(15. a4 $14)) 13. Nb5 $3 Bxb5 14. cxb5 Ne4 (14... c4 $6 15. bxc4 dxc4 (15...
Rxc4 $2 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. e4 Nc5 19. Qe2 $16) 16. Qc2 c3 17. Bc1 $1
Qc7 18. e4 $16) (14... cxd4 $2 15. Nxd4 Ne5 16. Qd2 Bc5 17. Rac1 $16 (17. e3
$16)) 15. Ne5 $1 (15. e3 f5 16. Rac1 $14 {White has the pair of bishops - he
is slightly better.}) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 f5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bxe4 Bxb2 19.
Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Rab1 Qf6 21. Rf1 Be5 22. Bg6 $16 *

