1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 c6 5. Qc2 Nbd7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. Nbd2
b6 ({After a move like} 8... Re8 {we can simply continue with} 9. e4 dxe4 10.
Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Nf6 12. Qe2 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ne5 $16 {Preventing ...e5
and opening up the g2-bishop. Black cannot even develop his bishop.}) 9. e4 Bb7
10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Qa4 Nb8 14. Bf1 $1 $16 {White
continues with his plan, not bothering about the pawn on a7.} ({After} 14. Qxa7
Bc6 $13 {the queen feels uncomfortable.}) 14... a6 15. Bd3 b5 16. Qd1 Nc6 17.
a3 (17. Nf1 {was also good; for example} Nb4 18. Bb1 Qc7 19. Ne3 $16) 17... Qb6
18. Nb3 a5 19. Be3 a4 20. Nbd2 (20. Nc5 $1 $16) 20... Na5 21. Nf1 (21. Bg5 $1
$16) 21... Nc4 (21... f5 $1 $13) 22. Bc1 Na5 (22... f6 $1 $132) 23. Bf4 Nc4 24.
Rb1 Ba6 25. h4 b4 ({After} 25... Nc7 26. Ng5 h6 27. Nh3 {followed by Qg4 would
be a typical way to attack.}) 26. Qe2 Nc7 27. Ng5 Bxg5 28. hxg5 Qxd4 29. Rbd1
Qxb2 30. Qh5 g6 31. Qh6 bxa3 32. Nh2 Ne8 33. Ng4 a2 34. Nf6+ Nxf6 35. gxf6 1-0

